Atlantic hurricane in 2011}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2014}}\n<!-- We should leave the disambiguation description succinct rather than make a half-paragraph summary about it. It's not very clean. -->\n{{Infobox hurricane\n| Name=Hurricane Irene\n| Type=hurricane\n| Year=2011\n| Basin=Atl\n| Image location=Hurricane Irene Aug 24 2011 1810Z.jpg\n| Image name=Hurricane Irene at peak intensity over the southern [[Bahamas]] on August&nbsp;24\n| Formed=August 21, 2011\n| Dissipated=August 30, 2011\n| Extratropical=August 28\n| 1-min winds=105\n| Pressure=942\n| Damages=14200\n| Fatalities=49 direct, 9 indirect\n| Areas=[[Hispaniola]], [[Lesser Antilles]], [[Greater Antilles]], [[Turks and Caicos]], [[Bahamas]], [[East Coast of the United States]], [[Vermont]] <small>([[Landfall]]s in [[North Carolina]], [[New Jersey]], [[New York (state)|New York]]</small>, [[Atlantic Canada]])\n| Hurricane season=[[2011 Atlantic hurricane season]]\n}}\n\n'''Hurricane Irene''' was a large and destructive [[tropical cyclone]] which affected much of the [[Caribbean]] and [[East Coast of the United States]] during late August 2011. The ninth [[tropical cyclone naming|named storm]], first hurricane, and first major hurricane of the [[2011 Atlantic hurricane season]], Irene originated from a well-defined [[Atlantic Ocean|Atlantic]] [[tropical wave]] that began showing signs of organization east of the [[Lesser Antilles]]. Due to development of [[atmospheric convection]] and a closed center of circulation, the system was designated as Tropical Storm Irene on August&nbsp;20, 2011. After intensifying, Irene made [[Landfall (meteorology)|landfall]] in [[St. Croix]] as a strong tropical storm later that day. Early on August&nbsp;21, the storm made a second landfall in [[Puerto Rico]]. While crossing the island, Irene strengthened into a [[Category 1 hurricane]]. The storm paralleled offshore of [[Hispaniola]], continuing to slowly intensify in the process. Shortly before making four landfalls in the Bahamas, Irene peaked as a {{convert|120|mph|km/h|abbr=on}} Category&nbsp;3 hurricane.\n\nThereafter, the storm slowly leveled off in intensity as it struck the Bahamas and then curved northward after passing east of [[Grand Bahama]]. Continuing to weaken, Irene was downgraded to a Category&nbsp;1 hurricane before making landfall on the [[Outer Banks]] of [[North Carolina]] on August&nbsp;27, becoming the first hurricane to make landfall in the United States since [[Hurricane Ike]] in 2008. Early on the following day, the storm re-emerged into the Atlantic from southeastern [[Virginia]]. Although Irene remained a hurricane over water, it weakened to a tropical storm while making yet another landfall in the [[Little Egg Inlet]] in southeastern [[New Jersey]] on August&nbsp;27. A few hours later, Irene made its ninth and final landfall in [[Brooklyn]], New York City. Early on August&nbsp;29, Irene transitioned into an [[extratropical cyclone]] while striking [[Vermont]], after remaining inland as a tropical cyclone for less than 12&nbsp;hours.\n\nThroughout its path, Irene caused widespread destruction and at least 49 deaths. Damage estimates throughout the United States are estimated near $13.5 billion, making Irene one of the costliest hurricanes on record in the country. In addition, monetary losses in the Caribbean and Canada were $830&nbsp;million and $130&nbsp;million respectively for a total of nearly $14.2 billion in damage.<ref name=\"csr-damagetotal\">{{cite news|last=Fieser|first=Erza|title=Hurricane Irene barrels toward US as Caribbean islands take stock of damage|url=http://www.csmonitor.com/World/Americas/2011/0825/Hurricane-Irene-barrels-toward-US-as-Caribbean-islands-take-stock-of-damage|accessdate=September 20, 2011|newspaper=[[The Christian Science Monitor]]|date=August 25, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite report|title=Telling the Weather Story|date=June 4, 2012|publisher=Insurance Bureau of Canada|accessdate=July 19, 2015|url-status=live|url=http://assets.ibc.ca/Documents/Studies/McBean_Report.pdf|format=PDF|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6a8hB4BMq?url=http://assets.ibc.ca/Documents/Studies/McBean_Report.pdf|archivedate=July 19, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Meteorological history==\n{{Storm path|Irene 2011 track.png}}\nOn August 15, 2011, a [[tropical wave]] exited the west African coast, and emerged into the [[Atlantic Ocean|Atlantic]], characterized by distinct low-level [[cyclonic rotation]] and deep tropical humidity.<ref name=\"twd-2p-15\">{{cite web|last=Walton|first=Corey|title=Tropical Weather Discussion|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/text/TWDAT/TWDAT.201108151746.txt|work=[[National Hurricane Center]]|accessdate=September 20, 2011|date=August 15, 2011}}</ref> It remained well-defined while moving steadily westward for several days to the south of the [[Cape Verde|Cape Verde Islands]], although at the time any notable [[atmospheric convection|convection]] occurred well to the southwest of its axis.<ref name=\"twd-2p-16\">{{cite web|last=Walton|first=Corey|title=Tropical Weather Discussion|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/text/TWDAT/TWDAT.201108161748.txt|work=[[National Hurricane Center]]|accessdate=September 20, 2011|date=August 16, 2011}}</ref> As the wave distanced itself from the islands, development of thunderstorms and showers in its proximity continued to remain scarce, and it became rather broad in appearance.<ref name=\"gtwo-2a-18\">{{cite web|last=Cangialosi|first=John|title=Graphical Tropical Weather Outlook|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/gtwo/atl/201108180537/index.php?basin=atl|work=[[National Hurricane Center]]|accessdate=September 20, 2011|date=August 18, 2011}}</ref> On August 19, the convective structure began to show signs of organization as the associated [[atmospheric pressure]] lowered, and with a progressively favorable environment situated ahead of the wave its chances of undergoing [[tropical cyclogenesis]] markedly increased.<ref name=\"twd-8a-19\">{{cite web|last=Tichacek|first=Michael|title=Tropical Weather Discussion|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/text/TWDAT/TWDAT.201108191159.txt|work=[[National Hurricane Center]]|accessdate=September 20, 2011|date=August 19, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"gtwo-8a-20\">{{cite web|last=Beven|first=Jack|title=Graphical Tropical Weather Outlook|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/gtwo/atl/201108201203/index.php?basin=atl|work=[[National Hurricane Center]]|accessdate=September 20, 2011|date=August 20, 2011}}</ref> The strong thunderstorm activity continued to become more pronounced around the main [[Low-pressure area|low-pressure feature]]. By August 20, the [[National Hurricane Center]] noted that [[tropical cyclone]] formation was imminent as the wave neared the [[Lesser Antilles]],<ref name=\"gtwo-2p-20\">{{cite web|last=Beven|first=Jack|title=Graphical Tropical Weather Outlook|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/gtwo/atl/201108201757/index.php?basin=atl|work=[[National Hurricane Center]]|accessdate=September 20, 2011|date=August 20, 2011}}</ref> and a [[Hurricane Hunters|reconnaissance aircraft]] confirmed the presence of a small surface circulation center just southwest of a burst of vigorous convection and unusually high [[Maximum sustained wind|sustained winds]], indicating sufficient organization for the cyclone to be upgraded into Tropical Storm Irene at 23:00 [[UTC]] that day.<ref name=\"id-7p-20\" />\n\nIrene was positioned about {{convert|190|mi|km|abbr=on}} east of [[Dominica]] in the [[Lesser Antilles]] when it was classified and named, along weakening [[high-pressure area|high pressure]] over the west-central Atlantic, inducing a roughly west-northwestward path for most of its journey through the eastern [[Caribbean]].<ref name=\"id-7p-20\">{{cite web|last1=Blake |first1=Eric |title=Tropical Storm Irene Special Discussion Number 1|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/2011/al09/al092011.discus.001.shtml|work=[[National Hurricane Center]]|accessdate=September 24, 2011|author2=Brennan, Michael|date=August 20, 2011}}</ref> Its mid-level circulation continued to become better established as hints of pronounced [[rainband|banding features]] curved north of the surface center.<ref name=\"id-11p-20\">{{cite web |last1=Blake |first1=Eric |title=Tropical Storm Irene Discussion Number 2|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/2011/al09/al092011.discus.002.shtml|work=[[National Hurricane Center]]|accessdate=September 24, 2011|author2=Brennan, Michael|date=August 20, 2011}}</ref> On August 21, the surface center reformed closer to the deepest convection; furthermore, an [[anticyclone]] aloft provided supportive [[outflow (meteorology)|outflow]] over the cyclone. With the improved structure, as well as light [[wind shear]] and high [[sea surface temperature]]s, Irene was forecast to strengthen to near hurricane force prior to landfall in [[Hispaniola]].<ref name=\"id-5a-21\">{{cite web|last=Stewart|first=Stacy|title=Tropical Storm Irene Discussion Number 1|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/2011/al09/al092011.discus.003.shtml|work=[[National Hurricane Center]]|accessdate=September 24, 2011|date=August 21, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"id-11a-21\">{{cite web|last=Pasch|first=Richard|title=Tropical Storm Irene Discussion Number 4|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/2011/al09/al092011.discus.004.shtml|work=[[National Hurricane Center]]|accessdate=September 24, 2011|date=August 21, 2011}}</ref> Over the subsequent day (August 22), while passing near the island of [[Saint Croix, U.S. Virgin Islands|Saint Croix]] in the [[U.S. Virgin Islands]],<ref name=\"ipa-8p-21\">{{cite web|last=Brennan|first=Michael|title=Tropical Storm Irene Intermediate Advisory Number 5A|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/2011/al09/al092011.public_a.005.shtml|work=[[National Hurricane Center]]|accessdate=September 24, 2011|date=August 21, 2011}}</ref> Irene traced toward [[Puerto Rico]], more northward than initially expected, where it underwent a considerable increase in strength and organization.<ref name=\"id-11p-21\">{{cite web|last=Brennan|first=Michael|title=Tropical Storm Irene Discussion Number 6|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/2011/al09/al092011.discus.006.shtml|work=[[National Hurricane Center]]|accessdate=September 24, 2011|date=August 21, 2011}}</ref> Hours later, Irene moved ashore, approaching from the southeast at landfall near [[Cayo Santiago|Punta Santiago]], [[Humacao, Puerto Rico]], with estimated sustained winds of {{convert|70|mph|km/h|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"tcu-130a-22\">{{cite web|last=Stewart|first=Stacy|title=Tropical Storm Irene Tropical Cyclone Update|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/2011/al09/al092011.update.08220530.shtml|work=[[National Hurricane Center]]|accessdate=September 24, 2011|date=August 22, 2011}}</ref> Despite the storm's interaction with land, [[weather radar|radar imagery]] showed a ragged [[Eye (cyclone)|eye]]-like feature, and [[Weather radar#Velocity|Doppler weather radar data]] indicated wind speeds in excess of [[Beaufort scale|hurricane force]]. Just after its initial landfall, Irene was accordingly upgraded to a [[Category 1 hurricane]], the first of the [[2011 Atlantic hurricane season]].<ref name=\"id-5a-22\">{{cite web|last=Stewart|first=Stacy|title=Hurricane Irene Discussion Number 7|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/2011/al09/al092011.discus.007.shtml|work=[[National Hurricane Center]]|accessdate=September 24, 2011|date=August 22, 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Irene goe 201108 h264 sm xo.ogv|thumb|right|Loop showing Irene's progress as viewed from the [[GOES 13|GOES-EAST]] satellite]]\n\nWith the hurricane then situated just north of the mountainous coast of [[Hispaniola]], the storm deepened little after reemerging over water, and any additional organization during the rest of the day was gradual.<ref name=\"id-5p-22\">{{cite web|last=Avila|first=Lixion|title=Hurricane Irene Discussion Number 9|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/2011/al09/al092011.discus.009.shtml|work=[[National Hurricane Center]]|accessdate=September 24, 2011|date=August 22, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"id-11p-22\">{{cite web|last=Brennan|first=Michael|title=Hurricane Irene Discussion Number 11|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/2011/al09/al092011.discus.011.shtml|work=[[National Hurricane Center]]|accessdate=September 24, 2011|date=August 22, 2011}}</ref> After briefly weakening on August 23,<ref name=\"id-5p-23\">{{cite web|last=Brown|first=Daniel|title=Hurricane Irene Discussion Number 14|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/2011/al09/al092011.discus.014.shtml|work=[[National Hurricane Center]]|accessdate=September 24, 2011|date=August 23, 2011}}</ref> however, Irene began to develop a distinct eye encircled by an area of deepening convection the next morning. Moving erratically through the southeast [[the Bahamas|Bahamas]] over very warm waters,<ref name=\"id-5a-24\">{{cite web |last1=Pasch |first1=Richard |title=Hurricane Irene Discussion Number 16 |url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/2011/al09/al092011.discus.016.shtml |work=[[National Hurricane Center]] |author2=Kimberlain, Todd |date=August 24, 2011 |accessdate=September 24, 2011}}</ref> Irene quickly expanded as its outflow aloft became very well established; the cyclone intensified into a Category 3 [[tropical cyclone scales#Atlantic and East Pacific|major hurricane]] as it recurved toward the northwest along a weakness in the [[subtropical ridge]].<ref name=\"id-5p-24\">{{cite web|last=Brown|first=Daniel|title=Hurricane Irene Discussion Number 18|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/2011/al09/al092011.discus.018.shtml|work=[[National Hurricane Center]]|accessdate=September 24, 2011|date=August 24, 2011}}</ref> The cyclone subsequently underwent a partial [[eyewall replacement cycle]], which resulted in some reduction in its winds. Although a distinct eye redeveloped for a few hours, it obscured once again soon thereafter; Irene was unable to recover from the cycle, with no further significant intensification expected thereafter.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wunderground.com/blog/JeffMasters/comment.html?entrynum=1902|author=Masters, Jeff|title=Irene's eyewall collapses; further intensification unlikely.|publisher=[[Weather Underground (weather service)|Weather Underground Blog]]|date=August 26, 2011|accessdate=August 26, 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Hurricane Irene's demise.jpg|thumb|left|240px|Hurricane Irene's remnants on August 30, in the process of being absorbed by another system.]]\nEarly on August 27, Irene further weakened to a Category 1 hurricane as it approached the [[Outer Banks]] of [[North Carolina]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/2011/al09/al092011.public_b.027.shtml |title=Hurricane Irene Intermediate Advisory Twenty-Seven B|author1=Beven, Jack |author2=Brennan, Michael |date=August 27, 2011|publisher=[[National Hurricane Center]]|accessdate=August 27, 2011}}</ref> At 7:30&nbsp;am EDT (11:30 UTC) the same day, Irene made landfall near [[Cape Lookout (North Carolina)|Cape Lookout]], on North Carolina's Outer Banks, with winds of {{convert|85|mph|km/h|abbr=on}}, but exhibited an unusually low pressure of 951 mbar, which is typically found in a category 3 hurricane.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/2011/al09/al092011.public_a.028.shtml|title=Hurricane Irene Intermediate Advisory Twenty-Eight A|last=Brown|first=Daniel|date=August 27, 2011|publisher=[[National Hurricane Center]]|accessdate=August 27, 2011}}</ref> After having tracked over land for about 10 hours, the eye of Irene became cloud-filled, although the center remained well-defined on radar images.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/2011/al09/al092011.discus.030.shtml |title=Hurricane Irene Discussion Number 30 |author1=Brown, Daniel |author2=Franklin, James |date=August 27, 2011|publisher=[[National Hurricane Center]]|accessdate=August 27, 2011}}</ref> Early in the evening of August 27, Irene re-emerged into the Atlantic near the southern end of the [[Chesapeake Bay]] in [[Virginia]] as a marginal Category 1 hurricane, slowly weakening as it continued northward and weakening to a tropical storm early on August 28.<ref name=\"advis30A\"/> Shortly before sunrise, at 5:35&nbsp;am EDT (0935 UTC) on August 28, Irene made a second landfall at [[Brigantine, New Jersey|Brigantine]] in southeastern [[New Jersey]] with winds of {{convert|70|mph|km/h|abbr=on}}<ref name=nhc>{{cite news|title=Tropical Cyclone Report - Hurricane Irene|quote=Irene then continued north-northeastward, just offshore of the Delmarva peninsula, and made another landfall very near Atlantic City, New Jersey, at Brigantine Island, at 0935 UTC 28 August. Although Irene's intensity at the New Jersey landfall was 60 kt, winds of that strength were confined to the waters east of the track of the center. |url={{NHC TCR url|id=AL092011_Irene}} |agency=[[National Hurricane Center]] |work= |date=2011-12-14 |accessdate=2014-09-22}}</ref> and soon after moved over water again, hugging the New Jersey coastline. About 3 1/2 hours later, Tropical Storm Irene made landfall with {{convert|65|mph|km/h|abbr=on}} winds in the [[Coney Island]] neighborhood of [[Brooklyn]], [[New York City|New York]].\n\nFollowing its final New York landfall, Irene moved northeast over [[New England]] while maintaining its strength, before it was declared an extratropical cyclone early on August 29, while its center was located near the New Hampshire/Vermont border.<ref name=\"tcr\">{{cite report|author=Avila, Lixion A|author2=Cangialosi, John|date=December 14, 2011|title=Tropical Cyclone Report: Hurricane Irene: August 21&nbsp;\u2013 28, 2011|publisher=United States National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration's National Weather Service|format=PDF|work=National Hurricane Center|accessdate=July 19, 2015|url={{NHC TCR url|id=AL092011_Irene}}|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6CVHoEYto?url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/data/tcr/AL092011_Irene.pdf|archivedate=November 27, 2012}}</ref> During that day, the system continued to move towards the northeast, before it was absorbed by a frontal system early on August 30.<ref name=\"tcr\"/>\n\n==Preparations==\n\n===Caribbean===\nIn response to the formation of Irene, [[Tropical cyclone warnings and watches|tropical storm warnings]] were issued for all of the [[Leeward Islands]] and [[Puerto Rico]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/2011/al09/al092011.public.001.shtml |title=Tropical Storm Irene Advisory Number One |date=August 20, 2011|accessdate=August 22, 2011|publisher=[[National Hurricane Center]]|first1=Eric|last1=Blake|first2=Michael|last2=Brennan}}</ref> Also in the Lesser Antilles, the storm's approach prompted authorities in the [[United States Virgin Islands|U.S. Virgin Islands]] to close off air- and seaports, as well as to open public shelters.<ref name=\"vidn\"/> As Irene was forecast to make landfall on [[Hispaniola]], a [[Tropical cyclone warnings and watches#Tropical Storm Watch|tropical storm watch]] was initially issued for the south coast of the [[Dominican Republic]], though it was upgraded to a [[Tropical cyclone warnings and watches#Hurricane Warning|hurricane warning]] on August 21, after strengthening was forecast.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/2011/al09/al092011.public.002.shtml |title=Tropical Storm Irene Advisory Number Two|date=August 21, 2011|accessdate=August 21, 2011|publisher=[[National Hurricane Center]]|first1=Eric|first2=Michael|last1=Blake|last2=Brennan}}</ref> In light of the expected intensification to hurricane status, a tropical storm warning was also issued for the northern coast fire of that country, while a tropical storm watch was put in effect for all of [[Haiti]]; the tropical storm warning for Puerto Rico was simultaneously upgraded to a [[Hurricane Watch|hurricane watch]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/2011/al09/al092011.public.003.shtml |title=Tropical Storm Irene Advisory Number Three|date=August 21, 2011|accessdate=August 21, 2011|publisher=[[National Hurricane Center]]|first=Stacy|last=Stewart}}</ref> Later that day, all of the Dominican Republic was placed under a hurricane warning, with the tropical storm watch for Haiti upgraded to a warning and a tropical storm watch initiated for the southeastern [[The Bahamas|Bahamas]] and the [[Turks and Caicos Islands]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/2011/al09/al092011.public.004.shtml |title=Tropical Storm Irene Advisory Number Four|date=August 21, 2011|accessdate=August 21, 2011|publisher=[[National Hurricane Center]]|first=Richard|last=Pasch}}</ref> As Irene's forecast track became justified, the latter watch was upgraded to a warning on August 22, while a hurricane watch was declared for the central Bahamas.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/2011/al09/al092011.public.006.shtml |title=Tropical Storm Irene Advisory Number Six|date=August 21, 2011|accessdate=August 21, 2011|publisher=[[National Hurricane Center]]|first=Richard|last=Pasch}}</ref>\n\n===Mainland United States===\nWith Irene's projected path fixed over much of the [[East Coast of the United States|United States East Coast]], over 65 million people from the Carolinas to northern New England were estimated to be at risk.<ref>{{cite news|title=65 million people on East Coast await Hurricane Irene's wrath|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/44285405|publisher=NBC News|accessdate=August 26, 2011|date=August 26, 2011}}</ref> Due to the threat, state officials, as well as utilities, transportation facilities, ports, industries, oil refineries, and nuclear power plants, promptly prepared to activate emergency plans; residents in the areas stocked up on food supplies and worked to secure homes, vehicles and boats.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/08/26/storm-irene-idUSN1E77O0RJ20110826|title=US East Coast in Irene's path, scrambles to prep|agency=[[Reuters]]|author=Reuters staff|date=August 25, 2011|accessdate=August 25, 2011|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61EepUrCL?url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2011/08/26/storm-irene-idUSN1E77O0RJ20110826|archivedate=August 26, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> States of emergency and hurricane warnings were declared for much of the East Coast, including [[North Carolina]],<ref name=\"wsjaug25\" /> [[Virginia]],<ref name=\"wsjaug25\" /><ref name=\"washpost26\" /> [[Maryland]],<ref name=\"washpost26\" /> [[Delaware]],<ref name=do /> the [[Washington, D.C.|District of Columbia]],<ref name=\"dc-emergency\">{{cite news|last=Craig|first=Tim|title=D.C. declares state of emergency as Hurricane Irene approaches|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/dc-wire/post/dc-to-declare-state-of-emergency-as-hurricane-irene-approaches/2011/08/26/gIQA4i5ZgJ_blog.html|work=Washington Post|accessdate=September 20, 2011|date=August 26, 2011}}</ref> [[Pennsylvania]],<ref name=\"abc27\">{{cite news|last=Rubkinam|first=Michael|title=Pa. gov declares state of emergency as Irene looms|url=http://www.abc27.com/story/15337522/hurricane-warning-issued-for-philly-as-irene-looms?clienttype=printable |work=[[WHTM-TV]]|accessdate=September 8, 2011}}</ref> [[New Jersey]],<ref name=\"wsjaug25\" /> [[New York (state)|New York]],<ref name=\"wsjaug25\" /> [[Connecticut]],<ref name=\"wsjblog\">{{cite news |last=Holthaus |first=Eric |title=Waiting for Irene: What to Expect When the Storm Arrives |url=https://blogs.wsj.com/metropolis/2011/08/26/hurricane-irene-new-yorks-hurricane-waiting-game/ |work=The Wall Street Journal |accessdate=August 26, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61Eet39fJ?url=http://blogs.wsj.com/metropolis/2011/08/26/hurricane-irene-new-yorks-hurricane-waiting-game/?mod=google_news_blog |archivedate=August 26, 2011 |url-status=live |date=August 26, 2011 }}</ref> [[Rhode Island]],<ref name=\"rigov\">{{cite press release|url=http://www.ri.gov/press/view/14589|title=Governor Lincoln D. Chafee Issues Declaration of Disaster Emergency|date=August 26, 2011|publisher=Rhode Island |accessdate=August 26, 2011|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61EevgQoj?url=http://www.ri.gov/press/view/14589|archivedate=August 26, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Massachusetts]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bostonherald.com/news/regional/view/20110826gov_patrick_declares_state_of_emergency_ahead_of_hurricane_irene/|title=Gov. Patrick declares state of emergency ahead of Hurricane Irene|agency=Associated Press|date=August 26, 2011|work=[[Boston Herald]]|accessdate=August 26, 2011|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61Eez92Tk?url=http://news.bostonherald.com/news/regional/view/20110826gov_patrick_declares_state_of_emergency_ahead_of_hurricane_irene/srvc%3Dhome%26position%3Drecent|archivedate=August 26, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Vermont]],<ref name=wcax /> [[New Hampshire]],<ref name=\"cnnliveblog\" /> and [[Maine]].<ref name=Mueller />\n\nIn advance of the storm, hundreds of thousands of people evacuated near coastal areas, and hundreds of shelters were prepared. Many gasoline stations in the region reported shortages due to the preparations for Irene.<ref name=\"gasshortage\">{{cite news|title=Irene bringing gasoline shortages, power outages|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/APca9d9b9f7e144a20a68030a81c592207|agency=[[Associated Press]]|work=The Wall Street Journal|accessdate=August 26, 2011|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61Ef3ks2U?url=http://online.wsj.com/article/APca9d9b9f7e144a20a68030a81c592207.html|archivedate=August 26, 2011|url-status=dead|date=August 27, 2011}}</ref> Six [[Major League Baseball]] games were postponed or moved to August 27 in doubleheaders, and one [[National Football League]] preseason game was postponed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bleacherbumsports.net/2011/08/26/update-irene-forces-saturday-sox-as-doubleheader/|title=Update: Irene forces Saturday Sox-A's doubleheader|last=Jackson|first=Scott|date=August 26, 2011|publisher=Bleacher Bum Sports|accessdate=August 26, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Clubs take precautions in advance of Irene|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?content_id=23770306|publisher=MLB.com|date=August 27, 2011|accessdate=August 27, 2011}}</ref><ref name=Giants>{{cite news|url=http://www.nypost.com/p/sports/giants/weather_won_change_jets_giants_game_9Hg3xsoWHc3Rq4s9dfceHK|title=Jets-Giants game moved to Saturday afternoon|date=August 25, 2011|work=The New York Post|accessdate=August 26, 2011}}</ref> [[The Barclays]] golf tournament was shortened<ref name=\"transithalt\" /> and three [[Major League Soccer]] games were postponed.<ref>{{cite news|last=Bell|first=Jack|title=Friday Update: M.L.S. Postpones 3 Games|url=http://goal.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/08/25/m-l-s-postpones-2-games-changes-starting-time-of-a-third/|work=The New York Times|accessdate=August 26, 2011|date=August 25, 2011}}</ref>\n[[File:Hurricane Irene Aug 27 2011 1910Z.jpg|thumb|left|Hurricane Irene shortly after landfall in the Outer Banks of North Carolina]]\n\n====Southeast====\n\nIn [[South Carolina]], Emergency Management was already on standby in [[Charleston County, South Carolina|Charleston]] and [[Dorchester County, South Carolina|Dorchester]] counties in preparation for September. On August 23, preparations were also being made in [[Beaufort County, South Carolina|Beaufort County]] as well.<ref name=\"cnnaug22\" /> The gondolas were removed from the [[Myrtle Beach SkyWheel]] attraction in preparation for tropical-storm-force winds.\n\nIn [[North Carolina]], a mandatory evacuation order was issued on August 23, for [[Ocracoke, North Carolina|Ocracoke Island]] and [[Hyde County, North Carolina|Hyde County]].<ref name=\"cnnaug22\">{{cite news|title=FEMA: Entire east coast should prepare for Hurricane Irene|url=http://www.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/americas/08/23/tropical.weather/|publisher=CNN|date=August 23, 2011|accessdate=August 22, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|agency=Associated Press|title=Breaking News: Evacuation Orders For Ocracoke|url=http://www.witn.com/home/headlines/128251773.html|accessdate=August 26, 2011|publisher=WITN|date=August 23, 2011}}</ref> Governor [[Bev Perdue]] declared a [[state of emergency]] on August 25, with hurricane and tropical storm watches posted for the state; a mandatory evacuation was issued for [[Carteret County, North Carolina|Carteret County]] and for all tourists of [[Dare County, North Carolina|Dare County]], though the latter was extended to include all residents by the next day.<ref name=\"wsjaug25\" /><ref name=\"carteretnc\">{{cite news|title=Coastal NC's Carteret County Orders Evacuations|url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/wireStory?id=14380541|agency=[[Associated Press]]|publisher=[[ABC News]]|accessdate=August 25, 2011}}{{Verify source|date=August 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"dare-county-bulletins\">{{cite web|title=Emergency Management Bulletins (Dare County, NC)|publisher=Dare County Government|date=August 26, 2011|url=http://www.darenc.com/EmgyMgmt/Alert/index.asp|accessdate=August 26, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111006214431/http://www.darenc.com/EmgyMgmt/Alert/index.asp|archive-date=October 6, 2011|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In addition, officials urged residents at the [[Bogue Banks]] to commence evacuations by 6&nbsp;am August 26, and tourists in [[Currituck County, North Carolina|Currituck County]] were advised to move inland.<ref name=\"carteretnc\" /><ref name=\"msnbcaug25\" /> [[Seymour Johnson Air Force Base]] planned to move jets to [[Barksdale Air Force Base]] in [[Louisiana]];<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/44257921|title=Hurricane Irene has NC base ready to move jets |publisher=MSNBC|date=August 24, 2011|accessdate=August 25, 2011}}{{dead link|date=November 2019|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> [[Marine Corps Air Station Cherry Point]] and [[Marine Corps Air Station New River]] both evacuated their aircraft as well.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hodge|first=Hope|title=New River aircraft evacuate in preparation for Irene|url=http://www.enctoday.com/articles/moves-94342-jdn-nears-new.html|publisher=ENCToday.com|accessdate=August 27, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111004222258/http://www.enctoday.com/articles/moves-94342-jdn-nears-new.html|archive-date=October 4, 2011|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[Progress Energy Inc|Progress Energy]] announced on August 26, it would have 800 more line workers and 250 tree cutters ready after Hurricane Irene.<ref name=\"ap-forbes-ncoutages\">{{cite news|title=NC utilities bracing for power outages inland |url=https://www.forbes.com/feeds/ap/2011/08/26/business-us-irene-nc-utilities-north-carolina_8645062.html |agency=[[Associated Press]] |work=Forbes |accessdate=August 26, 2011 |date=August 26, 2011 }}{{dead link|date=May 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> Officials at [[University of North Carolina at Wilmington|UNC-Wilmington]] issued a voluntary evacuation and enforced a curfew in response to the storm, interrupting move-in activities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wect.com/story/15335594/uncw-issues-voluntary-evacuation|title=UNCW issues voluntary evacuation and curfew|date=2011-08-05|publisher=[[WECT]].com|accessdate=August 21, 2013}}</ref> As low-level atmospheric [[Deformation (meteorology)#Stretching direction|confluence]] within the outer bands developed near the coast, a tornado watch was issued from north-northeast of [[Cape Hatteras]] to southwest of [[Wilmington, North Carolina|Wilmington]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Corfidi|first=Steve|title=Tornado Watch 809|url=http://www.spc.ncep.noaa.gov/products/watch/ww0809.html|publisher=[[Storm Prediction Center]]|accessdate=August 27, 2011|date=August 26, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110929184247/http://www.spc.ncep.noaa.gov/products/watch/ww0809.html|archivedate=September 29, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nVirginia Governor [[Bob McDonnell]] declared a state of emergency in preparation for any possible effects from the hurricane along coastlines. Authorities in the cities of [[Norfolk, Virginia|Norfolk]], [[Virginia Beach, Virginia|Virginia Beach]], [[Newport News, Virginia|Newport News]], [[Hampton, Virginia|Hampton]], and [[Portsmouth, Virginia|Portsmouth]] issued voluntary and mandatory evacuations for low-lying and oceanfront areas.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcwashington.com/news/local/Voluntary-Evacuations-in-Virginia-128429188.html|title=Voluntary Evacuations in Virginia|date=August 25, 2011|publisher=[[NBC]]|accessdate=August 25, 2011}}</ref> The city of [[Poquoson, Virginia|Poquoson]] ordered a mandatory evacuation for all of its citizens.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hampton.gov/media/media_releases/hurricane_irene_declaration.html|title=Hampton Declares State Of Emergency For Hurricane Irene|date=August 25, 2011|publisher=The City of Hampton|accessdate=August 26, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111001024426/http://www.hampton.gov/media/media_releases/hurricane_irene_declaration.html|archivedate=October 1, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Public storm shelters were opened in most the cities, and officials also prepared school buildings to accommodate evacuees.<ref name=\"cnnstatebystate\">{{cite news|title=State-by-state developments related to Hurricane Irene|url=http://www.cnn.com/2011/US/08/25/hurricane.irene.state.by.state/index.html?hpt=hp_c2|publisher=CNN|accessdate=August 26, 2011|date=August 25, 2011}}</ref> By August 25, dozens of vessels at the Norfolk and Newport News shipyards began to evacuate or prepare to weather the storm, including the carriers ''[[USS Enterprise (CVN-65)|Enterprise]]'', ''[[USS Dwight D. Eisenhower (CVN-69)|Dwight D. Eisenhower]]'', ''[[USS Harry S. Truman (CVN-75)|Harry S. Truman]]'', ''[[USS Theodore Roosevelt (CVN-71)|Theodore Roosevelt]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.navytimes.com/news/2011/08/navy-hurricane-irene-scatters-2nd-fleet-082511/|title=Ships flee Norfolk as Hurricane Irene nears|date=August 25, 2011|author=McMichael, William|publisher=[[Navy Times]]|accessdate=August 25, 2011}}</ref> and the construction site of the ''[[USS Gerald R. Ford (CVN-78)|Gerald R. Ford]]''. The [[United States Navy]] ordered ships to halt their operations and clear the warning zone.<ref name=\"msnbcaug25\"/> [[Fort Monroe]] Army base was evacuated on August 26; [[Joint Base Langley\u2013Eustis|Langley Air Force Base]] followed suit the next day, save essential personnel.<ref name=\"transithalt\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jble.af.mil/news/story.asp?id=123269595 |accessdate=August 26, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110826200832/http://www.jble.af.mil/news/story.asp?id=123269595 |archivedate=August 26, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n====Mid-Atlantic====\n[[File:Hurricane irene 082811 0832 edt.jpg|thumb|right|Satellite image of Irene making landfall in New York City.]]\nOn August 25, Maryland Governor [[Martin O'Malley]] declared a state of emergency in preparation for Irene.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.wmdt.com/story/15333364/maryland-declares-a-state-of-emergency|agency=Associated Press|title=Maryland Declares A State Of Emergency|date=August 25, 2011|publisher=WMDT-TV 47|accessdate=August 25, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928073606/http://www.wmdt.com/story/15333364/maryland-declares-a-state-of-emergency|archivedate=September 28, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The town of [[Ocean City, Maryland|Ocean City]] initiated \"phase one\" of its [[contingency plan]] that same day, which includes a mandatory evacuation order for international workforce students.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://oceancitymd.gov/blog/?p=1138|title=Ocean City Initiates Phase I of Emergency Plan|date=August 25, 2011|publisher=Town of Ocean City Maryland|accessdate=August 25, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110913110112/http://oceancitymd.gov/blog/?p=1138|archivedate=September 13, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|agency=WMDT-TV 47|title=Student Workers Ordered To Evacuate Ocean City|url=http://www.wmdt.com/story/15331250/student-workers-ordered-to-evacuate-ocean-city|accessdate=August 25, 2011|date=August 25, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928073612/http://www.wmdt.com/story/15331250/student-workers-ordered-to-evacuate-ocean-city|archivedate=September 28, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Hours later, phase three of the plan was instituted; it ordered a mandatory evacuation scheduled to start at midnight August 25, for all residents, with the requirement that everyone be evacuated by 5&nbsp;pm local time, August 26.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wmdt.com/story/15333538/mandatory-evacuation-declared-for-ocean-city|author=Hughes, Ryan|title=Mandatory Evacuation Declared For Ocean City|date=August 25, 2011|publisher=WMDT-TV 47|accessdate=August 25, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928073628/http://www.wmdt.com/story/15333538/mandatory-evacuation-declared-for-ocean-city|archivedate=September 28, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On August 26, [[Dorchester County, Maryland|Dorchester]] and [[Wicomico County, Maryland|Wicomico]] Counties declared states of emergency.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.docogonet.com/uploads/File/Proclamation%20State%20of%20Emergency%20Dorchester%20County.pdf|title=Dorchester County Council Issues Hurricane Irene State of Emergency|date=August 25, 2011|publisher=Dorchester County Government|accessdate=August 25, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928161910/http://www.docogonet.com/uploads/File/Proclamation%20State%20of%20Emergency%20Dorchester%20County.pdf|archive-date=September 28, 2011|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wicomicocounty.org/IRENE.htm|title=Wicomico County Executive Issues Hurricane Irene State of Emergency|date=August 25, 2011|publisher=Wicomico County Government|accessdate=August 25, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927023910/http://www.wicomicocounty.org/IRENE.htm|archivedate=September 27, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Certain geographic areas of [[Somerset County, Maryland|Somerset]] and Wicomico Counties, along with all mobile homes in Wicomico County, had mandatory evacuation orders put in effect.<ref>{{cite web|author=Thomas, Lauren|url=http://www.wmdt.com/story/15335649/phased-evacuation-issued-in-somorset-county-md|title=Phased Evacuation Issued In Somerset County, MD|date=August 26, 2011|publisher=WMDT-TV 47|accessdate=August 26, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928073633/http://www.wmdt.com/story/15335649/phased-evacuation-issued-in-somorset-county-md|archivedate=September 28, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wmdt.com/story/15337923/evacuations-ordered-in-parts-of-wicomico-county|author=Gilchrist, Lynette|title=Evacuations Ordered In Parts Of Wicomico County|date=August 26, 2011|publisher=WMDT-TV 47|accessdate=August 26, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928073706/http://www.wmdt.com/story/15337923/evacuations-ordered-in-parts-of-wicomico-county|archivedate=September 28, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Public shelters were made available in Dorchester, [[Somerset County, Maryland|Somerset]], [[Wicomico County, Maryland|Wicomico]], and [[Worcester County, Maryland|Worcester]] Counties.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.delmarvanow.com/article/20110826/NEWS01/110826013/Local-shelter-information-by-county |title=Local Shelter Information by County|date=August 26, 2011|publisher=Daily Times|accessdate=August 26, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Delaware]], Governor [[Jack Markell]] ordered visitors to evacuate the [[Delaware beaches]] effective 6:00&nbsp;pm on August 25. In addition, he declared a state of emergency; shelters were scheduled to open throughout the state on August 26.<ref name=do>{{cite web|accessdate=August 26, 2011|title=Gov. Markell declares state of emergency|publisher=[[The News Journal]]|date=August 25, 2011|url=http://www.delawareonline.com/article/20110825/NEWS/110825045/Gov-Markell-declares-state-of-emergency|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61EkWzzGS?url=http://www.delawareonline.com/article/20110825/NEWS/110825045/Gov-Markell-declares-state-of-emergency|archivedate=August 26, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Cape May&nbsp;\u2013 Lewes Ferry]] across [[Delaware Bay]] also suspended service for late August 27, through August 28, in response to the pending arrival of the hurricane.<ref name=kyw>{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.cbslocal.com/2011/08/25/state-of-emergency-declared-in-new-jersey-ahead-of-hurricane-irene/|title=Evacuations Ordered In Parts Of Atlantic, Cape May And Ocean Counties Ahead Of Hurricane Irene|date=August 25, 2011|publisher=[[KYW-TV]]|location= Philadelphia|accessdate=August 26, 2011|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61Eka0J3A?url=http://philadelphia.cbslocal.com/2011/08/25/state-of-emergency-declared-in-new-jersey-ahead-of-hurricane-irene/|archivedate=August 26, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> Toll operations on [[Delaware Route 1]] were halted in order to optimize evacuation rates along highways. Transit services were expected to be shut down on August 27 and 28, while bridges over the [[Chesapeake and Delaware Canal]] and the [[Indian River (Delaware)|Indian River]] were closed due to high wind.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.delawareonline.com/article/20110826/NEWS/110826025/Markell-orders-evacuation-residents-along-coast-Hurricane-Irene-threatens-state|title=Markell orders evacuation of residents along coast|work=The News Journal|author=Montgomery, Jeff|date=August 26, 2011|accessdate=August 26, 2011|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61EkdRuZk?url=http://www.delawareonline.com/article/20110826/NEWS/110826025/Markell-orders-evacuation-residents-along-coast-Hurricane-Irene-threatens-state|archivedate=August 26, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=do2>{{cite web|accessdate=August 29, 2011|title=Irene leaves flooding, wind damage in its path|publisher=[[The News Journal]]|date=August 25, 2011|url=http://www.delawareonline.com/article/20110827/NEWS/110827032/Irene-leaves-flooding-wind-damage-its-path}}</ref> A tornado watch was issued for Delaware in association with Irene at 10:40&nbsp;am August 27.<ref name=\"twatchdel\">{{cite web|last=Weiss|title=Storm Prediction Center Tornado Watch 811|url=http://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/watch/ww0811.html|publisher=[[Storm Prediction Center]]|accessdate=August 27, 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Irene Boarded Windows.jpg|right|thumb|A restaurant boards up in preparation for Irene in [[Ocean City, New Jersey]]]]\nIn [[Washington, D.C.]], the forecast arrival of Hurricane Irene caused postponement of the planned August 28 dedication ceremony for the [[Martin Luther King, Jr. National Memorial]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2011/US/08/25/dc.king.memorial|title=Dedication of King memorial postponed due to Irene|accessdate=August 26, 2011|date=August 25, 2011|publisher=CNN}}</ref> In anticipation of the storm, thousands of sandbags were prepared for placement at flood-prone [[Washington Metro]] station entrances.<ref name=\"washpost26\">{{cite news|title=East Coast braces for Hurricane Irene; warning area expanded|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/east-coast-braces-for-hurricane-irene-warning-area-expanded/2011/08/26/gIQAH2uAgJ_story_1.html|date=August 26, 2011|work=The Washington Post|accessdate=August 26, 2011|first=Steve|last=Hendrix}}</ref> [[Amtrak]] service from [[Union Station (Washington, D.C.)|Washington's Union Station]] southward was cancelled from August 26, until August 28.<ref name=\"wsjaug25\">{{cite news|title=U.S. East Coast Braces as Irene Batters Bahamas|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424053111904875404576530023246645268|work=The Wall Street Journal|date=August 26, 2011|accessdate=August 25, 2011|first=Valerie|last=Bauerlein}}</ref>\n\nIn eastern [[Pennsylvania]], the ground was already saturated with water when the hurricane arrived, since the preceding month had been the wettest ever recorded.<ref name=\"MyFoxPhilly01\">{{cite web|last=Weiss|title=Irene Downgraded To Tropical Storm|url=http://www.myfoxphilly.com/dpp/news/local_news/irene-makes-brief-landfall-in-new-jersey-082811|publisher=[[MyFoxPhilly]]|accessdate=August 30, 2011}}</ref> Philadelphia mayor [[Michael Nutter]] expressed concern that there could be severe devastation in the city and surrounding areas,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.knowledge-center.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/Case-Study-Hurricane-Irene-and-T-S-Lee-Final.pdf |title=Creating Unsurpassed Situational Awareness During Hurricane Irene and Tropical Storm Lee |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131021200301/http://www.knowledge-center.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/Case-Study-Hurricane-Irene-and-T-S-Lee-Final.pdf |archivedate=2013-10-21 |accessdate=February 13, 2014}}</ref> and Governor [[Tom Corbett]] declared a state of emergency in Pennsylvania.<ref>{{cite web|last=Rubinkam|first=Michael|title=Pa. Gov. Corbett declares state of emergency|url=http://6abc.com/archive/8327974/|publisher=[[WPVI-TV]]|accessdate=August 27, 2015}}</ref> The [[SEPTA|Southeastern Pennsylvania Transportation Authority]] decided to halt all commuter rail service after midnight August 28.<ref name=\"transithalt\" /> On August 26, Philadelphia's mayor announced there would be no mandatory evacuations for the city, but urged residents to be prudent and to take action and leave should conditions warrant.<ref>{{cite news|title=Hurricane Irene continues path towards New York, Philadelphia, Boston and the rest of the Northeast|url=https://articles.washingtonpost.com/2011-08-26/national/35271732_1_hurricane-irene-dangerous-storm-surge-tropical-storm|accessdate=21 October 2013|newspaper=Times|date=26 August 2013}}</ref> Officials prepared to open three large shelters on the evening of August 27, capable of holding up to 6,000 people. The Philadelphia International Airport closed at 10:30&nbsp;pm on Saturday and remained closed until Monday.<ref name=do2/> In [[Marcus Hook, Pennsylvania|Marcus Hook]], along the [[Delaware River]], the [[Sunoco]] oil refinery preemptively lowered its production rate by 25&nbsp;percent, to {{convert|140000|oilbbl/d|m3/d}}.<ref name=\"sunocoreduced\">{{cite news|last1=Schneyer|first1=Joshua|author2=McGurty, Janet|title=UPDATE 1-NE energy suppliers brace for disruptions from Irene|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/08/26/storm-irene-operations-idUSN1E77P1O320110826 |publisher=Reuters |accessdate=August 26, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61Ekjev6v?url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2011/08/26/storm-irene-operations-idUSN1E77P1O320110826 |archivedate=August 26, 2011 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n[[File:GrandCentralTerminalEmpty.jpg|thumb|right|[[Grand Central Terminal]] stands empty following shut down of the [[Metro-North Railroad]].]]\nIn [[New Jersey]], Governor [[Chris Christie]] declared a [[state of emergency]] on August 25,<ref name=tsl>{{cite web|last=Gibson|first=Ginger|accessdate=August 25, 2011 |title=As Hurricane Irene nears, Gov. Christie declares a state of emergency to mobilize National Guard |work=[[The Star-Ledger]]|date=August 25, 2011|url=http://www.nj.com/news/index.ssf/2011/08/as_hurricane_irene_approaches.html}}</ref> with President Obama reaffirming the declaration nationally by August 27.<ref>{{cite news|last=Spoto|first=Mary Ann|title=President Obama declares state of emergency for N.J.|newspaper=[[The Star-Ledger]]|date=August 27, 2011|url=http://www.nj.com/news/index.ssf/2011/08/president_obama_declares_state.html|accessdate=August 27, 2011}}</ref> Mandatory evacuations were ordered for all of [[Cape May County, New Jersey|Cape May County]] and all [[Atlantic County, New Jersey|Atlantic County]] shore communities east of [[U.S. Route 9 in New Jersey|Route 9]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pressofatlanticcity.com/news/breaking/cape-may-county-atlantic-county-and-long-beach-island-evacuations/article_8cfa7bfc-cf08-11e0-aac8-001cc4c002e0.html|title=Cape May County, Atlantic County and Long Beach Island evacuations ordered; coast under hurricane watch|work=[[Press of Atlantic City]]|author=Watson, Sarah|date=August 25, 2011|accessdate=August 25, 2011}}</ref> prompting [[Atlantic City, New Jersey|Atlantic City]]'s first evacuation in history.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pressofatlanticcity.com/mobi/storm/atlantic-city-officials-urge-everyone-to-get-off-island-as/article_f282ae80-cfef-11e0-adc4-001cc4c002e0.html|title=Atlantic City officials urge everyone to get off island as city faces first evacuation in history|work=[[Press of Atlantic City]]|date=August 26, 2011|accessdate=August 26, 2011}}</ref> About 1,500 [[New Jersey Army National Guard|National Guard]] troops were deployed in New Jersey. One National Guard outfit was deployed to flood-prone Manville, NJ, (which was also devastated by Hurricane Floyd in 1999) A couple of National Guardsman attempted to drive two of their deep-water-capable [[Family of Medium Tactical Vehicles|FMTV]]s through the flooding, but the floodwaters were too deep. The vehicles were overtaken by the waters beneath a dipping Conrail underpass on South Main Street. The Guardsmen were photographed and videotaped by onlookers above them on the train bridge, and both photos and videos went viral over social media.<ref name=autogenerated1>James Barron, [https://www.nytimes.com/2011/08/28/nyregion/new-yorkers-warned-of-possible-electrical-shutdown.html \"New York City Shuts Down Amid Flooding Fears\"] (August 27, 2011), ''The New York Times''.</ref> Mandatory evacuations were also ordered for all of [[Long Beach Island]] in [[Ocean County, New Jersey|Ocean County]] and the [[Barnegat Peninsula]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pressofatlanticcity.com/news/breaking/mandatory-evacuation-of-long-beach-island-begins-at-a-m/article_8d2db1fe-cf5b-11e0-b019-001cc4c03286.html|title=Mandatory evacuation of Long Beach Island begins at 8&nbsp;am Friday|work=Press of Atlantic City|author=Weaver, Donna|date=August 25, 2011|accessdate=August 25, 2011}}</ref> To relieve evacuation traffic, toll operations were temporarily suspended on the [[Garden State Parkway]] south of the [[Raritan River]] and on the [[Atlantic City Expressway]].<ref name=\"cnnstatebystate\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.app.com/article/20110825/NJNEWS10/308250030/NJ-IRENE-UPDATES-Parkway-tolls-suspended-8-m-Friday-aid-evacuations|title=NJ Irene Updates: Parkway tolls to be suspended at 8&nbsp;am Friday to aid evacuations|work=Asbury Park Press|date=August 25, 2011|accessdate=August 26, 2011}}</ref> Residents of low-lying areas of [[Hudson County, New Jersey|Hudson County]] along the [[North River (Hudson River)|Hudson River]] and [[Upper New York Bay]] were advised to evacuate.<ref>{{Citation | last = Conti | title = Jersey City, Hoboken and Bayonne have varying levels of evacuation orders for Hurricane Irene | newspaper = The Jersey Journal | date = August 27, 2011 | url = http://www.nj.com/jjournal-news/index.ssf/2011/08/jersey_city_hoboken_and_bayonn.html |accessdate=September 14, 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[Governor of New York]] [[Andrew Cuomo]] declared a state of emergency on August 26,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/08/25/hurricane-irene-new-york_n_937101.html|title=New York Declares State Of Emergency For Hurricane Irene|work=[[The Huffington Post]]|date=August 25, 2011|accessdate=August 25, 2011|first=Simon|last=McCormack}}</ref> and that day issued a mandatory evacuation order for low-lying areas of New York City.<ref name=\"cnnliveblog\" /><ref name=\"evac-order-nyc\">{{cite web|title=New York City Hurricane Evacuation Zones|url=http://www.nyc.gov/html/oem/downloads/pdf/hurricane_map_english.pdf|publisher=NYC.gov|accessdate=August 26, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110912165708/http://www.nyc.gov/html/oem/downloads/pdf/hurricane_map_english.pdf|archive-date=September 12, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> A day prior, New York City Mayor [[Michael Bloomberg]] had announced that the city would prepare to create \"an enormous shelter system\" for residents without access to higher ground.<ref name=\"bloombergstatement\">{{cite news|last=Goldman|first=Henry|title=Irene May Require NYC Evacuations|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-25/irene-may-require-evacuations-of-some-new-york-city-areas-bloomberg-says.html|date=August 25, 2011|publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]]|accessdate=August 25, 2011}}</ref> President Barack Obama issued a state of emergency declaration for the New York metropolitan area, freeing federal disaster funds, and tasking the [[Federal Emergency Management Agency]] and the [[Department of Homeland Security]] to coordinate disaster relief efforts.<ref>{{cite news|title=Obama: Emergency for NY as Irene approaches|url=https://www.wsj.com/news/articles/SB10001424053111904875404576533732485689842?mod=WSJ_WSJ_US_News_3&mg=reno64-wsj|accessdate=August 28, 2011|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|date=August 26, 2011|agency=Associated Press}}</ref> Cuomo deployed 2,000 National Guard troops to assist police, the [[Metropolitan Transportation Authority]] (MTA) and the Port Authority in New York and [[Long Island]].<ref name=autogenerated1 /> Possible rising seawater levels from storm surge and a predicted high tide led to a complete shutdown of the MTA, the nation's largest mass transit system. All [[New York City Subway|subway]], bus, and commuter rail service in New York City was halted<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.myfoxny.com/dpp/news/local_news/staten_island/hurricane-irene-could-shut-down-entire-nyc-transit-system-20110825-akd|title=Hurricane Irene Could Shut Down Entire NYC Transit System|publisher=[[WNYW]]|date=August 25, 2011|accessdate=August 25, 2011}}</ref> at noon on August 27.<ref name=\"transithalt\">{{cite news|title=Live blog: New York, Philadelphia, New Jersey to halt transit services|url=http://news.blogs.cnn.com/2011/08/26/live-blog-irene-weakens-slightly|publisher=CNN|date=August 26, 2011|accessdate=August 26, 2011}}</ref> Four area hospitals began evacuating patients on August 26;<ref name=\"cnnliveblog\">{{cite news|title=Live blog: Irene's winds 'extremely dangerous' at 105 mph|url=http://news.blogs.cnn.com/2011/08/26/live-blog-irene-weakens-slightly/|publisher=CNN|date=August 26, 2011|accessdate=August 25, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"transithalt\" /><ref name=\"cnnstatebystate\" /> sixteen nursing homes and adult care facilities were also evacuated.<ref name=\"cnnstatebystate\" /> The [[New York International Fringe Festival]] cancelled all performances for August 27, and 28, as did all Broadway shows for those days.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/153978-UPDATED-Hurricane-Irene-Prompts-Cancellation-of-All-Broadway-Shows-Aug-27-28 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120913234608/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/153978-UPDATED-Hurricane-Irene-Prompts-Cancellation-of-All-Broadway-Shows-Aug-27-28 |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 13, 2012 |title=UPDATED: Hurricane Irene Prompts Cancellation of All Broadway Shows Aug. 27\u201328; Off-Broadway Also Impacted |last=Jones |first=Kenneth |date=August 26, 2011 |publisher=Playbill |accessdate=August 26, 2011 }}</ref> The [[United States Tennis Association]] cancelled special events planned for the [[2011 US Open (tennis)|2011 US Open]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Rossingh|first=Danielle|title=National Tennis Center to Close on Eve of U.S. Open; Kids' Day Canceled|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-26/national-tennis-center-to-close-on-eve-of-u-s-open-kids-day-canceled.html|accessdate=August 27, 2011|publisher=Bloomberg L.P.|date=August 26, 2011}}</ref>\n\n====New England====\n[[File:HurricaneIrene 2011 BefdordBasinVessels.jpg|thumb|Vessels riding out the storm in Bedford Basin near Halifax, Nova Scotia]]\nSouthern [[Connecticut]], along the [[Long Island Sound]], had a hurricane warning in place as of August 27, while northern Connecticut had a tropical storm warning. [[Governor of Connecticut|Governor]] [[Dannel Malloy]] declared a state of emergency<ref name=\"wsjblog\" /> and the state's emergency operations center was fully activated. As of 11&nbsp;a.m. on August 26, about 33,000 sandbags had been distributed to state residents. Bridgeport sustained heavier damages and many parts of south Groton had numerous power outages which took weeks to get up back and running.{{Citation needed|date=August 2011}}\n\nIn [[Rhode Island]], the Army Corps of Engineers closed the [[Fox Point Hurricane Barrier]] in anticipation that the hurricane would make a direct strike on [[Providence, Rhode Island|Providence]].\n\nIn [[Massachusetts]], [[Governor of Massachusetts|Governor]] [[Deval Patrick]] declared a state of emergency on August 26, activated 500 [[Massachusetts National Guard]] troops, and also planned to activate an additional 2,000 troops the following day in preparation for the storm.<ref>{{cite news|last=Kamp|first=Jon|title=Massachusetts Governor Declares State Of Emergency Ahead Of Irene|url=https://www.wsj.com/article/BT-CO-20110826-712270.html|accessdate=August 26, 2011|newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|date=August 26, 2011|agency=Dow Jones Newswires|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61Efmhm2J?url=http://online.wsj.com/article/BT-CO-20110826-712270.html|archivedate=August 26, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> In an unprecedented move, the [[Massachusetts Bay Transit Authority|MBTA]] suspended all metropolitan Boston public transportation at 8:00&nbsp;am on August 28.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.boston.com/news/local/massachusetts/articles/2011/08/28/mbta_suspends_service_on_sunday/|title=MBTA to suspend service at 8&nbsp;am Sunday|work=The Boston Globe|date=August 27, 2011|accessdate=August 28, 2011}}{{Verify source|date=August 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Vermont]], [[Governor of Vermont|Governor]] [[Peter Shumlin]] declared a state of emergency on August 27, in preparation for the hurricane's arrival.<ref name=wcax>\"[http://www.wcax.com/story/15344823/governor-declares VT Governor declares State of Emergency] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140108001517/http://www.wcax.com/story/15344823/governor-declares |date=January 8, 2014 }}\" (August 27, 2011). [[WCAX-TV]].</ref> In a joint statement, Vermont electric utilities announced that they planned to have extra staff on hand.<ref>Dave Gram, \"[http://www.chron.com/news/article/Vermont-braces-for-hurricane-due-Sunday-2142571.php Vermont braces for hurricane due Sunday]\" (August 26, 2011). Associated Press.</ref> The [[National Weather Service]] stated that it anticipated {{convert|2|\u2013|5|in|mm}} of rain on the [[Champlain Valley]] and western Vermont and {{convert|3|\u2013|7|in|mm}} in the [[Green Mountains]] and eastern Vermont, with the risk of flooding near streams and rivers and an anticipated sustained [[wind speed]]s of {{convert|30|\u2013|45|mph}} and gusts of up to {{convert|45|\u2013|65|mph}}, causing significant tree damage and damage to [[Overhead power line|power lines]].<ref>\"[http://www.burlingtonfreepress.com/article/20110826/NEWS02/110826003/Updated-forecast-Vermont-Hurricane-Irene?odyssey=tab|topnews|text|FRONTPAGE Updated forecast for Vermont on Hurricane Irene\" (August 26, 2011). ''Burlington Free Press''.]</ref>\n\nIn [[Maine]], [[Governor of Maine|Governor]] [[Paul LePage]] declared a state of emergency on August 26, in preparation for the expected arrival of Hurricane Irene on August 28.<ref name=Mueller /> Canadian utility and line workers were dispatched to Maine to assist in reinforcing the state's electrical infrastructure.<ref name=Mueller>{{cite news|last=Mueller|first=Tim|title=Maine under state of emergency; Canadian utilities sending workers|url=http://www.pressherald.com/news/maine-under-state-of-emergency_-canadian-utilities-sending-workers_2011-08-27.html|accessdate=August 27, 2011|newspaper=[[Portland Press]]|date=August 27, 2011}}</ref> Ten shelters were to be opened in Maine.<ref>J. Hemmerdinger, [http://www.pressherald.com/news/Businesses-prepare-for-Irene.html \"Groups prepare to open hurricane shelters\"] (August 28, 2011). ''Maine Sunday Telegram''.</ref>\n\n===Canada===\n\nNear [[Halifax Regional Municipality|Halifax]], Nova Scotia, Canada, numerous large local and ocean-going vessels anchored in [[Bedford Basin]] to ride out the storm.{{Citation needed|date=August 2011}}\n{{clear}}\n\n==Impact==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"float:right; margin:0 0 0.5em 1em; float:right;\"\n|+ Deaths and damage by region\n|-\n! Region !! Direct || Indirect || Damage<br />(USD) || class=\"unsortable\"|Sources\n|-\n| [[Bahamas]] || {{Sort|0|None}} || {{Sort|0|None}} || {{ntsp|40000000||$}} ||{{EM-DAT}}<ref name=\"BahamasDamage\">{{cite web|publisher=Caribbean360|date=October 7, 2011|accessdate=October 14, 2011|title=Millions in Hurricane Irene insurance claims in The Bahamas|url=http://www.caribbean360.com/index.php/news/bahamas_news/508804.html#axzz1alk3eBHs}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Canada]] || {{Sort|0|None}} || {{nts|1}} || {{ntsp|130000000||$}} ||<ref name=ibcdamage>{{cite report|title=Telling the Weather Story |date=June 4, 2012 |publisher=Insurance Bureau of Canada |accessdate=June 4, 2012 |url=http://www.ibc.ca/en/Natural_Disasters/documents/McBean_Report.pdf |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105163055/http://ibc.ca/en/Natural_Disasters/documents/McBean_Report.pdf |archivedate=November 5, 2012 }}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Dominican Republic]] || {{nts|5}} || {{Sort|0|None}} || {{ntsp|30000000||$}} ||<ref name=\"tcr\"/><ref name=\"emdat\"/>\n|-\n| [[Haiti]] || {{nts|3}} || {{Sort|0|None}} || {{ntsh|0}} Unknown ||<ref name=\"tcr\"/>\n|-\n| [[United States]] || {{nts|40}} || {{nts|8}} || {{ntsp|13500000000||$}} ||<ref name=\"tcr\"/><ref name=\"Costliest TC's\">{{cite report|archivedate=January 26, 2018|url-status=live|date=January 12, 2018|title=Costliest U.S. tropical cyclones tables update|accessdate=January 12, 2018|publisher=United States National Hurricane Center|url=https://www.nhc.noaa.gov/news/UpdatedCostliest.pdf|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6wlV5fBNV?url=https://www.nhc.noaa.gov/news/UpdatedCostliest.pdf|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Puerto Rico]] || {{nts|1}} || {{Sort|0|None}} || {{ntsp|500000000||$}} ||<ref name=\"tcr\"/><ref name=\"emdat\"/>\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n| '''Totals:''' || '''49''' || '''9''' || {{ntsp|{{#expr:40000000+130000000+30000000+13500000000+500000000}}||$}} ||\n|}\n\n===Lesser Antilles===\nFollowing its path through the northeastern Caribbean, Irene spread tropical storm conditions across all of the [[Leeward Islands]], causing overall little damage but flooded some low-lying areas.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/weather/2011/08/21/tropical-storm-irene-growing-strength-in-caribbean/|title=Tropical Storm Irene barrels toward Puerto Rico|date=August 21, 2011|accessdate=August 23, 2011|agency=[[Associated Press]]|publisher=[[Fox News Channel|Fox News]]|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61EkqtfiZ?url=http://www.foxnews.com/weather/2011/08/21/tropical-storm-irene-growing-strength-in-caribbean/|archivedate=August 26, 2011|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> To the south, strong thunderstorms and showers spread over [[Martinique]], though most of the activity occurred prior to development into a tropical cyclone.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.martinique.franceantilles.fr/actualite/environnement/de-fortes-pluies-orageuses-cette-nuit-20-08-2011-123000.php|title=De fortes pluies orageuses cette nuite|date=August 22, 2011|accessdate=August 22, 2011|work=Journal France-Antilles|publisher=France Antilles Martinique|author=Staff writer|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61EktHjN9?url=http://www.martinique.franceantilles.fr/actualite/environnement/de-fortes-pluies-orageuses-cette-nuit-20-08-2011-123000.php|archivedate=August 26, 2011|url-status=live|language=fr}}</ref> In spite of the center tracking just north of [[Guadeloupe]]'s island [[Grande-Terre]], the strongest effects were brought on by Irene's outer [[rainband]]s. Tropical-storm-force winds generated brief rough seas, with peak [[Wind wave|wave]] heights of no more than {{convert|18|ft|m|abbr=on}}. Accompanying intermittent torrents swept through much of the territory, but overall rainfall was moderate; precipitation totals of between {{convert|3.1|and|4.7|in|mm|abbr=on}} fell in [[Basse-Terre Island|Basse-Terre]] during the event.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guadeloupe.franceantilles.fr/actualite/education-sante-environnement/retour-au-vert-22-08-2011-135501.php|title=Retour au vert|date=August 22, 2011|accessdate=August 22, 2011|work=Journal France-Antilles|publisher=France Antilles Guadeloupe|author=Staff writer|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61EkwUGlK?url=http://www.guadeloupe.franceantilles.fr/actualite/education-sante-environnement/retour-au-vert-22-08-2011-135501.php|archivedate=August 26, 2011|url-status=live|language=fr}}</ref> Due to the storm conditions, [[LIAT]] was forced to suspend all of its flights in [[Antigua]] for early August 22.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.antiguaobserver.com/?p=63332 |title=Tropical Storm Irene forces LIAT to suspend services in and out of Antigua |author=CMC |work=Antigua Observer |publisher=Observer Publications Limited |date=August 21, 2011 |accessdate=August 23, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61EkzhSyC?url=http://www.antiguaobserver.com/?p=63332 |archivedate=August 26, 2011 |url-status=dead |author-link=Caribbean Media Corporation }}</ref>\n\nPassing near the [[British Virgin Islands]] while strengthening, Irene brought gusty winds and heavy precipitation to the territory; however, resultant property damage was minimal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.virginislandsnewsonline.com/news/irene-passes-no-major-damage-reported|title=Irene passes, no major damage reported|publisher=Virgin Islands News Online|date=August 22, 2011|accessdate=August 22, 2011|author=Staff reporter|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61ElGy3Bw?url=http://www.virginislandsnewsonline.com/news/irene-passes-no-major-damage-reported|archivedate=August 26, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> A lightning strike over [[Necker Island (British Virgin Islands)|Necker Island]] sparked a large fire at one of business magnate [[Richard Branson]]'s resort homes, but all of its guest occupants\u2014including British actress [[Kate Winslet]]\u2014were able to exit the area.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2011/SHOWBIZ/celebrity.news.gossip/08/22/branson.house.fire/index.html?eref=mrss_igoogle_cnn |title=Fire destroys private-island home of Virgin head Richard Branson |date=August 22, 2011 |accessdate=August 23, 2011 |publisher=CNN |author=CNN Wire Staff |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61ElAj742?url=http://edition.cnn.com/2011/SHOWBIZ/celebrity.news.gossip/08/22/branson.house.fire/index.html?eref=mrss_igoogle_cnn |archivedate=August 26, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> Irene crossed [[Saint Croix, U.S. Virgin Islands]] as a strong tropical storm on August 21, though relatively calm winds associated with the passage of its center were recorded over the island. To the north in [[Saint Thomas, U.S. Virgin Islands|Saint Thomas]], storm conditions became progressively worse; sustained gale-force winds swept across the territory, with a gust of up to {{convert|68|mph|km/h|abbr=on}} recorded at 21:20 UTC. Upon impact, the winds and inclement weather caused scattered power outages across all islands.<ref name=\"vidn\">{{cite web|url=http://virginislandsdailynews.com/news/irene-s-eye-crosses-st-croix-1.1191673|title=Irene's eye crosses St. Croix|date=August 22, 2011|accessdate=August 23, 2011|first1=Joy|last1=Blackburn|first2=Daniel|last2=Shea|work=[[The Virgin Islands Daily News]]|publisher=[[Times-Shamrock Communications]]|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61ElE2i0e?url=http://virginislandsdailynews.com/news/irene-s-eye-crosses-st-croix-1.1191673|archivedate=August 26, 2011|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Wide-scale assessments confirmed light damage to public schools, mostly confined to debris and leaks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wtjx.org/newsline340/storm-assessments-show-minimal-damage-sustained-hurricane-irene|title=Storm Assessments Show Minimal Damage Sustained From Hurricane Irene|date=August 25, 2011|accessdate=August 27, 2011|author=Newsline 340|publisher=[[WTJX-TV]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110914033157/http://www.wtjx.org/newsline340/storm-assessments-show-minimal-damage-sustained-hurricane-irene|archive-date=September 14, 2011|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Greater Antilles===\n\n====Puerto Rico====\n[[File:Composite radar image 20110822.jpg|thumb|right|Last radar image of Irene from San Juan, before the radar went out]]\nAcross Puerto Rico, heavy rains caused extensive damage to roads while hurricane-force winds toppled many trees and utility poles, which led more than 1&nbsp;million residences without power.<ref name=elregional>{{cite web|url=http://www.elregionaldelzulia.com/Noticias/avance.asp?ID=4951|title=Hurac\u00e1n \"Irene\" deja da\u00f1os a su paso por Puerto Rico|date=August 22, 2011|accessdate=August 22, 2011|work=El Regional del Zulia|publisher=El Regional del Zulia C.A|author=Deutsche Presse-Agentur|language=es|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928032724/http://www.elregionaldelzulia.com/Noticias/avance.asp?ID=4951|archivedate=September 28, 2011|df=mdy-all|author-link=Deutsche Presse-Agentur}}</ref><ref name=Forbes>{{cite news|author=Coto, Danica|work=Forbes|date=August 22, 2011|accessdate=August 22, 2011|title=Hurricane Irene slams Puerto Rico; could hit US|url=https://www.forbes.com/feeds/ap/2011/08/22/general-tropical-weather_8634568.html|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61Ez3Nquv?url=http://www.forbes.com/feeds/ap/2011/08/22/general-tropical-weather_8634568.html|archivedate=August 27, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> President [[Barack Obama]] declared a state of emergency.<ref name=\"nydn1\">{{cite web|last=Boyle |first=Christina |date=August 23, 2011 |title=Category two Hurricane Irene on track to hit Florida, Georgia and Carolinas by the weekend |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/world/2011/08/23/2011-08-23_category_two_storm_hurricane_irene_on_track_to_hit_florida_georgia_and_carolinas.html |work=[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]] |accessdate=August 23, 2011 |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/619qOsNQf?url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/world/2011/08/23/2011-08-23_category_two_storm_hurricane_irene_on_track_to_hit_florida_georgia_and_carolinas.html |archivedate=August 23, 2011 }}</ref> About 121,000 customers were cut off from potable water service at the height of the storm, and islandwide at least 771 people had to take shelter.<ref name=elregional /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elnuevodia.com/sinserviciodeaguapotablemasdecienmilabonados-1046469.html|title=Sin servicio de agua potable m\u00e1s de cien mil abonados|date=August 22, 2011|accessdate=August 22, 2011|first=Gerardo|last=Alvarado|publisher=Grupo Ferr\u00e9-Rangel|work=[[El Nuevo D\u00eda]]|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61Ez7hIAO?url=http://www.elnuevodia.com/sinserviciodeaguapotablemasdecienmilabonados-1046469.html|archivedate=August 27, 2011|url-status=live|language=es}}</ref> At higher elevations, winds estimated by [[weather radar|radar]] neared {{convert|111|mph|km/h|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite web|author=Stewart, Stacy|publisher=National Hurricane Center|date=August 22, 2011|accessdate=August 22, 2011|title=Hurricane Irene Tropical Cyclone Update|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/2011/al09/al092011.update.08220958.shtml?}}</ref> The highest amounts of precipitation fell across eastern parts of the territory; in [[Gurabo, Puerto Rico|Gurabo]], a peak total of {{convert|22.04|in|mm|abbr=on}} was recorded.<ref>{{cite book|author2=Hydrometeorological Prediction Center|url=http://www.wpc.ncep.noaa.gov/tropical/rain/irene2011prfilledrainblk.gif|title=Hurricane Irene \u2013 August 21\u201324, 2011|author=Roth, David M|date=August 26, 2011|publisher=United States National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration's National Weather Service|accessdate=August 26, 2011}}</ref> Several rivers burst their banks as a consequence of the rains, causing additional flooding.<ref name=Forbes /> The agricultural sector also suffered losses from the storm, particularly near the location of landfall. High winds uprooted crop plants, and several coffee and banana plantations sustained minor damage.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elnuevodia.com/reportepreliminardedanosenlaagricultura-1046331.html|title=Reporte preliminar de da\u00f1os en la agricultura|date=August 22, 2011|accessdate=August 22, 2011|first=Andrea|last=Mart\u00ednez|publisher=Grupo Ferr\u00e9-Rangel|work=[[El Nuevo D\u00eda]]|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61EzCvZYj?url=http://www.elnuevodia.com/reportepreliminardedanosenlaagricultura-1046331.html|archivedate=August 27, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> Of the plantations, the most affected were situated in [[Yabucoa, Puerto Rico|Yabucoa]] and [[Maunabo, Puerto Rico|Maunabo]], where severe flooding washed out copious amounts of banana crop.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elnuevodia.com/azotealassiembrasenmaunaboyyabucoa-1046856.html|title=Azote a las siembras en Maunabo y Yabucoa|date=August 23, 2011|accessdate=August 23, 2011|first=Joanisabel|last=Gonz\u00e1lez|publisher=Grupo Ferr\u00e9-Rangel|work=[[El Nuevo D\u00eda]]|language=es}}</ref> The rains continued to fall for hours into the wake of the storm, prompting the issuance of flood watches.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elnuevodia.com/seesperanunas4pulgadasmasdelluviaentodopuertorico-1046838.html|title=Se esperan unas 4 pulgadas m\u00e1s de lluvia en todo Puerto Rico|date=August 22, 2011|accessdate=August 23, 2011|first=Yanira H.|last=Cabiya|publisher=Grupo Ferr\u00e9-Rangel|work=[[El Nuevo D\u00eda]]|language=es}}</ref> In total, Irene affected over 1,500 people in Puerto Rico, and one driver was killed after their vehicle was caught in swollen currents.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.telesurtv.net/secciones/noticias/96843-NN/huracan-irene-en-puerto-rico-deja-al-menos-un-muerto-y-mil-500-damnificados/|title=Hurac\u00e1n Irene en Puerto Rico deja al menos un muerto y mil 500 damnificados|date=August 23, 2011|accessdate=August 24, 2011|publisher=[[TeleSUR]]|author1=Staff|author2=AFP|language=es|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110826232132/http://www.telesurtv.net/secciones/noticias/96843-NN/huracan-irene-en-puerto-rico-deja-al-menos-un-muerto-y-mil-500-damnificados/|archivedate=August 26, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref>{{deprecated inline|certain=y|November 2019}} Preliminary estimates indicate structural damage could be as high as $500 million (USD), with additional losses due to the three-day labor suspensions pinned at over $60.4 million (USD).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elnuevodia.com/losdanosascenderiana$500millones-1048917.html|title=Los da\u00f1os ascender\u00edan a $500 millones|first=Gloria R.|last=Kuilan|publisher=Grupo Ferr\u00e9-Rangel|work=[[El Nuevo D\u00eda]]|date=August 25, 2011|accessdate=August 25, 2011|language=es}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Irene 2011 Puerto Rico rainfall.gif|thumb|left|Hurricane Irene's rainfall across Puerto Rico]]\nOffshore near [[Culebra, Puerto Rico|Culebra Island]], a sailboat was reported to have sunk due to rough seas prior to landfall in mainland Puerto Rico. Gale-force winds felled fences and shattered windows, with a flying object piercing through one residence. A total of 46&nbsp;locals sought refuge to ride out the storm, but one family required post-storm shelter after the roof to their home was lost.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elnuevodia.com/unvelerohundidoydestrozosenresidenciasdejaelhuracanireneensupasoporculebra-1046534.html|date=August 22, 2011|title=Un velero hundido y destrozos en residencias deja el hurac\u00e1n Irene en su paso por Culebra|accessdate=August 22, 2011|first=Israel R.|last=S\u00e1nchez|publisher=Grupo Ferr\u00e9-Rangel|work=[[El Nuevo D\u00eda]]|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61EzV4SMv?url=http://www.elnuevodia.com/unvelerohundidoydestrozosenresidenciasdejaelhuracanireneensupasoporculebra-1046534.html|archivedate=August 27, 2011|url-status=live|language=es}}</ref> On the island of [[Vieques, Puerto Rico|Vieques]], similar sustained winds of {{convert|51|mph|km/h|abbr=on}} were recorded, as well as some gusts of up to {{convert|71|mph|km/h|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/2011/al09/al092011.update.08220519.shtml|title=Tropical Storm Irene Tropical Cyclone Update|last=Stewart|first=Stacy|date=August 22, 2011|publisher=[[National Hurricane Center]]|accessdate=August 22, 2011}}</ref> Some power and telephone service cutoffs were reported, and the island's airport halted its operations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elnuevodia.com/azotoduroavieques-1046902.html|title=Azot\u00f3 duro a Vieques|date=August 23, 2011|accessdate=August 23, 2011|first=Natalia R.|last=Bartolomei|publisher=Grupo Ferr\u00e9-Rangel|work=[[El Nuevo D\u00eda]]|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61EzZPROW?url=http://www.elnuevodia.com/azotoduroavieques-1046902.html|archivedate=August 27, 2011|url-status=live|language=es}}{{verify source|date=September 2011}}</ref>\n\n====Hispaniola====\nSkirting barely north past [[Hispaniola]], the large storm produced gales and prolonged precipitation in the [[Dominican Republic]], displacing over 37,700 people and leaving at least 88 communities isolated in its wake.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eldia.com.do/nacionales/2011/8/24/60598/Desplazados-por-las-lluvias-aumentan-a-37-743|title=Desplazados por las lluvias aumentan a 37,743|first=Johanna|last=Garc\u00eda|work=El D\u00eda|date=August 25, 2011|accessdate=August 26, 2011|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61ElicY7Q?url=http://eldia.com.do/nacionales/2011/8/24/60598/Desplazados-por-las-lluvias-aumentan-a-37-743|archivedate=August 26, 2011|url-status=dead|language=es|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=damage>{{cite web |url=http://www.diarioadiario.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=5868:hay-31900-desplazados-y-85-comunidades-aisladas&catid=111:actualidad&Itemid=492 |title=Hay 31,900 desplazados y 85 comunidades aisladas |work=Diario @ Diario |date=August 24, 2011 |accessdate=August 24, 2011 |author=Redacci\u00f3n |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61ElkUKdu?url=http://www.diarioadiario.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=5868:hay-31900-desplazados-y-85-comunidades-aisladas&catid=111:actualidad&Itemid=492 |archivedate=August 26, 2011 |url-status=live |language=es }}</ref> Accompanying [[storm surge]] affected roughly 200 homes and prompted evacuations along the northern coastlines.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://diarioadiario.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=5849:desplazaos-superan-los-12-hay-25-comunidades-aisladas&catid=98:destacada |title=Desplazados superan los 12 mil; hay 25 comunidades aisladas |work=Diario @ Diario |date=August 24, 2011 |accessdate=August 24, 2011 |author=Redacci\u00f3n |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61Elo1HOK?url=http://diarioadiario.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=5849:desplazaos-superan-los-12-hay-25-comunidades-aisladas&catid=98:destacada |archivedate=August 26, 2011 |url-status=live |language=es }}</ref> The strongest winds also occurred in northern [[Cibao]], where they felled multiple trees and toppled utility poles. Swollen rivers, creeks, and streams caused widespread residential flooding and damage to roads; saturated soil in the region triggered mudslides, causing additional disruptions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.listindiario.com.do/la-republica/2011/8/23/200891/Irene-deja-danos-en-costa-norte |title=Irene deja da\u00f1os en costa norte |first1=Manuel |last1=Gilbert |first2=Ricardo |last2=Santana |work=[[List\u00edn Diario]] |publisher=List\u00edn Diario |date=August 23, 2011 |accessdate=August 24, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61ElpzjIk?url=http://www.listindiario.com.do/la-republica/2011/8/23/200891/Irene-deja-danos-en-costa-norte |archivedate=August 26, 2011 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Despite its distance, Irene produced extreme rainfall in southern parts of the country that led to many secondary effects. Resultant floods combined with two overflown rivers swept through much of [[San Crist\u00f3bal, Dominican Republic|San Crist\u00f3bal]], causing one bridge to collapse under the rushing waters.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.listindiario.com.do/la-republica/2011/8/23/200891/Irene-deja-danos-en-costa-norte |publisher=Fundaci\u00f3n Macroeconodata |title=Lluvias causan muertes y destruyen puentes en el Sur |work=Peri\u00f3dico 7 D\u00edas |date=August 24, 2011 |accessdate=August 24, 2011 |author=Staff writer |language=es |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61ElpzjIk?url=http://www.listindiario.com.do/la-republica/2011/8/23/200891/Irene-deja-danos-en-costa-norte |archivedate=August 26, 2011 }}</ref> The flooding produced at least two drown victims in that area, both later confirmed dead. Elsewhere, another fatality occurred in [[Cambita Garabitos]], and six others were listed as missing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.almomento.net/news/127/ARTICLE/94303/2011-08-24.html|title=Hay tres muertos, 31 mil 900 personas desplazadas y da\u00f1os diversos por Irene|date=August 24, 2011|accessdate=August 24, 2011|first1=Ram\u00f3n|last1=Urb\u00e1ez|first2=Jos\u00e9 A.|last2=Thomas|first3=Carlos|last3=Corporan|work=Almomento.net|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61Elu8Abg?url=http://www.almomento.net/news/127/ARTICLE/94303/2011-08-24.html|archivedate=August 26, 2011|url-status=dead|language=es|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Heavy rains also fell across [[La Altagracia Province]], where one person in [[Hig\u00fcey (city)|Hig\u00fcey]] went missing and hundreds were evacuated. Most of the damage in the region occurred due to flooded rivers, with some agricultural losses reported.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.primicias.com.do/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=11585 |title=Una persona desaparecida y 45 comunidades incomunicadas dej\u00f3 Irene regi\u00f3n Este |date=August 24, 2011 |accessdate=August 25, 2011 |first=Manuel A. |last=Vega |work=Primicias |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61Elx1qq5?url=http://www.primicias.com.do/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=11585 |archivedate=August 26, 2011 |url-status=dead |language=es }}</ref> The excess surface waters overwhelmed and damaged some 170 inlets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elnacional.com.do/nacional/2011/8/26/93114/INDRHI-reporto-Irene-dano-170-tomas|title=INDRHI report\u00f3 Irene da\u00f1\u00f3 170 tomas|date=August 26, 2011|publisher=[[El Nacional (Santo Domingo)|El Nacional]]|accessdate=August 28, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111002041635/http://www.elnacional.com.do/nacional/2011/8/26/93114/INDRHI-reporto-Irene-dano-170-tomas|archive-date=October 2, 2011|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In all, Irene affected at least 2,292 households according to preliminary reports, with 16 houses rendered beyond repair.<ref name=damage /> The associated monetary losses surmounted [[Dominican peso|RD$]]1 billion (US$30 million) in the wake of the event.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.noticiassin.com/2011/08/danos-causados-por-irene-en-el-pais-se-llevan-alrededor-de-mil-millones-de-pesos/|title=Da\u00f1os causados por Irene en el pa\u00eds se llevan alrededor de mil millones de pesos|date=August 29, 2011|accessdate=August 31, 2011|work=Noticias SIN|first=Joaqu\u00edn|last=Carabollo|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120508123154/http://www.noticiassin.com/2011/08/danos-causados-por-irene-en-el-pais-se-llevan-alrededor-de-mil-millones-de-pesos/|archive-date=May 8, 2012|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn northeastern [[Haiti]], the prolonged precipitation overflowed rivers and produced surface floods and damaging landslides across multiple road sections.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metropolehaiti.com/metropole/full_une_fr.php?id=19409 |title=Ir\u00e8ne provoque des inondations dans le Nord Ouest |publisher=[[Radio M\u00e9tropole]] |author1=LLM |author2=Staff writer |date=August 23, 2011 |accessdate=August 26, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61Em25GKJ?url=http://www.metropolehaiti.com/metropole/full_une_fr.php?id=19409 |archivedate=August 26, 2011 |url-status=live |language=fr }}</ref> About 500 residents in risk zones evacuated while some sought shelter, but only one of more than 160 evacuation sites required usage.<ref name=UNNews>{{cite web |url=https://www.un.org/apps/news/story.asp?NewsID=39371&Cr=Haiti&Cr1= |title=Haiti escapes serious damage from Hurricane Irene, UN reports |date=August 24, 2011 |publisher=[[UN News Centre]] |accessdate=August 25, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61Em4whTT?url=http://www.un.org/apps/news/story.asp?NewsID=39371&Cr=Haiti&Cr1= |archivedate=August 26, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> Rough surge produced high coastal flooding, with some reports of thousands of damaged homes. In the vicinity of [[Port-au-Prince]], brisk winds blew down many refuge tents home to victims from the major [[2010 Haiti earthquake|January 12, 2010 earthquake]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ahora.cu/english/sections/international/4825-hurricane-irene-wreaks-havoc-in-haiti.html|title=Hurricane Irene wreaks havoc in Haiti|date=August 24, 2011|accessdate=August 26, 2011|author=Prensa Latina|work=[[Ahora (newspaper)|Ahora]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110830064914/http://www.ahora.cu/english/sections/international/4825-hurricane-irene-wreaks-havoc-in-haiti.html|archive-date=August 30, 2011|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all|author-link=Prensa Latina}}</ref> Overall, officials indicated impact was less severe than initially feared; the storm only left isolated flood damage in its wake, particularly throughout northern parts of the country.<ref name=UNNews /> However, two people lost their lives after being caught in swollen rivers, and four others suffered injuries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lefigaro.fr/flash-actu/2011/08/25/97001-20110825FILWWW00515-l-ouragan-irene-fait-2-morts-en-haiti.php|title=L'ouragan Ir\u00e8ne fait 2 morts en Ha\u00efti|date=August 25, 2011|accessdate=August 26, 2011|author=Agence France-Presse|work=Le Figaro |publisher=[[Dassault Group]]|language=fr|author-link=Agence France-Presse}}</ref>\n\n====Cuba====\nAs Irene was tracking through the Bahamas, the outer bands of the storm dropped light rainfall in eastern [[Cuba]]. The cities of [[Moa, Cuba|Moa]] and [[Sagua de T\u00e1namo, Cuba|Sagua de T\u00e1namo]] in [[Holgu\u00edn Province]] reported {{convert|2.36|in|mm|abbr=on}} of rain. However, the average rainfall throughout the Holgu\u00edn Province did not exceed {{convert|0.20|in|mm|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ahora.cu/english/sections/holguin/4833-irene-does-not-leave-much-rain-in-holguin.html|title=Irene Does not Leave much Rain in Holguin|last=Gonz\u00e1lez|first=Rubicel|date=August 25, 2011|publisher=ahora.cu|accessdate=August 26, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110828152001/http://www.ahora.cu/english/sections/holguin/4833-irene-does-not-leave-much-rain-in-holguin.html|archive-date=August 28, 2011|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Some damage occurred throughout [[Guant\u00e1namo Province]], where rough surf and rains caused flooding in [[Baracoa]]. In addition, waves of {{convert|10|to|12|ft|m}} high were seen in Gibara, Holgu\u00edn, on Wednesday 24, when Irene's eye was located between Acklins and Crooked Islands, Bahamas, just {{convert|178|mi|km}} northeast of the city. The strong waves, combined with high tide, caused a slight coastal flooding.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/2011/08/24/2373354/huracan-irene-causa-danos-en-baracoa.html|title=Hurac\u00e1n Irene causa da\u00f1os en Baracoa, Cuba|date=August 24, 2011|accessdate=August 27, 2011|work=[[The Miami Herald]]|publisher=[[The McClatchy Company]]|author=El Nuevo Herald|language=es|author-link=El Nuevo Herald}}</ref>\n\n===Turks and Caicos and the Bahamas===\n'''Turks and Caicos:''' On August 24, Irene passed over the [[British Overseas Territories|British Overseas Territory]] of [[Turks and Caicos Islands]] at Category 1 strength. The hurricane produced high winds that blew off roofs and downed power lines throughout the territory.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sdentertainer.com/news/hurricane-irene-update/ |title=Hurricane Irene Update |last=Fernandez |first=Irma |date=August 25, 2011 |work=San Diego Entertainer |accessdate=August 25, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61EhwiEGL?url=http://www.sdentertainer.com/news/hurricane-irene-update/ |archivedate=August 26, 2011 }}</ref> In [[Cockburn Town]], residences reported loss of power, and light poles were toppled. Many homes on [[Grand Turk Island]] also reported a loss of electricity during Irene's passage, although structural damage in the area was limited.<ref name=foxnews>{{cite news |url=http://www.foxnews.com/weather/2011/08/23/hurricane-irene-marks-first-big-us-threat-in-years/ |title=Irene Weakens to Category 1 Hurricane, But Remains Big Threat to U.S. |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=August 23, 2011 |publisher=Fox News Channel |accessdate=August 25, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61Ei0z1ic?url=http://www.foxnews.com/weather/2011/08/23/hurricane-irene-marks-first-big-us-threat-in-years/ |archivedate=August 26, 2011 }}</ref> The strongest of the rains and gusts occurred in [[Providenciales]], where light wind damage was reported to roofs and resorts.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.travelweekly.com/Caribbean-Travel/Irene-drenches-Turks-and-Caicos,-Bahamas/|title=Irene drenches Turks and Caicos, Bahamas|last=Myers|first=Gay N.|date=August 24, 2011|work=[[Travel Weekly]]|publisher=Northstar Travel Media|accessdate=August 27, 2011}}</ref> The Grand Turk cruise port also sustained some minor damage from the storm, but operations resumed three days after impact.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://travel.usatoday.com/cruises/post/2011/08/hurricane-irene-grand-turk-port-damage-itinerary-changes/416763/1|title=Hurricane Irene damages Grand Turk cruise port|last=Bleiberg|first=Larry|date=August 26, 2011|work=USA Today|publisher=[[Gannett Company]]|accessdate=August 27, 2011}}</ref>\n\n'''Bahamas:''' A major hurricane, Irene trekked right through [[the Bahamas]], with its eye making landfall on several of the islands.<ref name=\"wsjaug25\" /> A peak wind gust of about {{convert|140|mph|km/h|abbr=on}} was recorded at the height of the storm, and localized heavy rains of up to {{convert|13|in|mm}} fell in the area.<ref name=worst>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.com/articles/204523/20110826/hurricane-irene-2011-bahamas-nema-nassau-cat-island.htm|title=Hurricane Irene: The Bahamas picks up the pieces after devastating storm|date=August 26, 2011|accessdate=August 26, 2011|publisher=The International Business Times Inc|work=[[International Business Times]]|author=Staff reporter}}</ref> The extreme winds damaged at least 40 homes on [[Mayaguana|Mayaguana Island]], and dozens of homes on [[Acklins]] were completely obliterated.<ref name=\"msnbcaug25\">{{cite web|title=More flee ahead of Irene as track forecast shifts|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/44270712|publisher=NBC News|date=August 26, 2011|accessdate=August 25, 2011}}</ref> On the latter island, the hurricane reportedly wiped out 90 percent of the [[Lovely Bay, Acklins|Lovely Bay]] settlement.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenassauguardian.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=12388|work=The Naussau Guardian |date=August 25, 2011 |accessdate=August 25, 2011 |first=Chester |last=Robards |title=Irene devastates Southeastern Bahamas |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61Ei9eEVj?url=http://www.thenassauguardian.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=12388 |archivedate=August 26, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Similar winds tore off the roof and shattered the windows out of a high school on [[Crooked Island, Bahamas|Crooked Island]], where wind gusts as high as {{convert|99|mph|km/h|abbr=on}} were reported.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-14641567|title=Hurricane Irene hammers Bahamas islands|date=August 25, 2011|work=BBC News|accessdate=August 25, 2011|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61EiCm3Q7?url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-14641567|archivedate=August 26, 2011}}</ref> As well, a local church on the island partially collapsed due to the storm.<ref name=CNN>{{cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/americas/08/25/hurricane.bahamas|title='Awesome' hurricane rips through Bahamas' 700 islands|publisher=CNN|author=CNN Wire Staff|date=August 25, 2011|accessdate=August 25, 2011|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61EiFxhxy?url=http://edition.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/americas/08/25/hurricane.bahamas/|archivedate=August 26, 2011}}</ref> The worst of the destruction occurred in [[Cat Island, Bahamas|Cat Island]], characterized by widespread shattered glass and torn houses. In all, the storm caused \"millions of dollars\" worth in structural damage on the island, and left many homeless.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tribune242.com/news/08272011_tt-cat-island_news_pg12--13|title=Davis: Irene caused millions of dollars in damage to Cat Island|date=August 27, 2011|accessdate=August 28, 2011|first=Taneka|last=Thompson|work=The Tribune|location=India|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/62xGwYXis?url=http://www.tribune242.com/news/08272011_tt-cat-island_news_pg12--13|archivedate=November 4, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Across [[New Providence]] and [[Grand Bahama]], only limited impact occurred as Irene remained well offshore; businesses operations were scheduled to return to normal shortly after the storm. Nationwide, the damage was estimated at $40&nbsp;million.<ref name=\"BahamasDamage\"/> Despite the overall extensive structural damage inflicted, there were no reports of fatalities on the islands in the wake of disaster.<ref name=CNN />\n\n===United States===\n[[File:Irene 2011 rainfall.gif|thumb|right|245px|Storm total rainfall from Hurricane Irene]]\nGales from Irene affected nearly all of the Eastern Seaboard, extending from Florida to New England and as far inland as central New York and central Pennsylvania, affecting all or large parts of 15 states and the District of Columbia. The winds, combined with soil saturation due to the extreme amounts of precipitation in many of the impacted areas both from Irene and from previous thunderstorms, uprooted countless trees and power lines along the storm's path. Roughly 7.4 million homes and businesses lost electrical power, with approximately 3.3 million still without power as of August 30, three days after landfall.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/44305129|title=Vermont, N.J. rivers still rising even after Irene|publisher=[[NBC News]]|author=Staff reporters|date=August 29, 2011|accessdate=August 29, 2011}}</ref> Coastal areas suffered extensive flood damage following its potent storm surge, with additional freshwater flooding reported in many areas. The storm spawned scattered tornadoes, causing significant property damage as evidenced by destroyed homes. In the [[Northeastern United States|northeastern region]], more than ten rivers measured record flood heights at their [[hydrograph]]s.<ref>{{cite web|last=Masters|first=Jeffrey|title=Irene's 1-in-100 year rains trigger deadly flooding|url=http://www.wunderground.com/blog/JeffMasters/comment.html?entrynum=1908|work=Weather Underground|publisher=Jeff Masters' WunderBlog|accessdate=September 14, 2011}}</ref> Rivers in at least six Northeastern states reached [[hundred-year flood]] levels, while the flooding in [[Greene County, New York]] was described as [[500-year flood|five-hundred-year-flood conditions]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Jonsson|first=Patrik|title=Aftermath of Irene: budget-straining cleanup and lives 'turned upside down'|url=http://www.csmonitor.com/USA/2011/0829/Aftermath-of-Irene-budget-straining-cleanup-and-lives-turned-upside-down|accessdate=August 29, 2011|newspaper=The Christian Science Monitor|date=September 14, 2011}}</ref> Flooding in [[Schoharie County, New York]] was also reported by the National Weather Service in Albany, New York as [[500-year flood|five-hundred-year-flood conditions]]. Throughout its path in the contiguous United States, Irene caused approximately $13.5 billion (2011 USD) in damage and 47 deaths.<ref name=\"Costliest TC's\"/><ref name=\"ABC6\">{{cite news|last=WPVI-TV|first=DT|title=The 44 victims of Hurricane Irene|url=http://abclocal.go.com/wpvi/story?section=news/local&id=8333317|accessdate=September 14, 2011|newspaper=6ABC|date=August 31, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news1130.com/news/world/article/271380--irene-kills-at-least-21-people|title=Irene kills at least 21 people|author=Staff writer|date=August 28, 2011|accessdate=August 29, 2011|publisher=[[Rogers Communications]]|work=[[CKWX|News1130]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120405190029/http://www.news1130.com/news/world/article/271380--irene-kills-at-least-21-people|archive-date=April 5, 2012|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n====Southeast====\n\n=====Florida=====\nThough Irene spared Florida from a direct hit, its outernmost rainbands produced squalls and intermittent torrents along the state's eastern coastlines. Brisk winds produced scattered power outages<ref name=\"WPTV\" />{{failed verification|date=October 2011}} and waves reaching as high as {{convert|12|ft|m|abbr=on}};<ref name=\"WPTV\" /> rough surf in the [[Boynton Inlet]] injured at least eight people,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wptv.com/dpp/news/region_s_palm_beach_county/boynton_beach/eight-people-injured-on-ocean-boulevard-when-their-jetty-is-hit-by-waves|title=Eight people injured by Irene's waves after being swept off a Boynton Beach jetty|last=Axelbank|first=Evan|date=August 26, 2011|publisher=WPTV|accessdate=August 27, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928180922/http://www.wptv.com/dpp/news/region_s_palm_beach_county/boynton_beach/eight-people-injured-on-ocean-boulevard-when-their-jetty-is-hit-by-waves|archivedate=September 28, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and two surfers were killed offshore [[Volusia County, Florida|Volusia County]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/2011-08-27/news/os-surfer-killed-hurricane-irene-20110827_1_rough-surf-hurricane-irene-central-florida-deaths|title=Hurricane Irene's rough surf kills two off Florida coast, officials say|date=August 27, 2011|accessdate=August 27, 2011|publisher=[[Orlando Sentinel]]|last=Weiner|first=Jeff}}</ref> Elsewhere, in [[Lantana, Florida|Lantana]], large waves sweeping over seawalls went on to destroy a lifeguard tower.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.palmbeachpost.com/storm/scattered-rain-51scattered-rain-51-mph-wind-gusts-hit-south-1786999.html|title=Scattered rain, 51-mph wind gusts hit South Florida as Irene slams Bahamas, aims at Carolinas|date=August 25, 2011|accessdate=August 25, 2011|publisher=[[The Palm Beach Post]]|last=Kleinberg|first=Eliot|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61EfXzQC3?url=http://www.palmbeachpost.com/storm/eight-injured-in-boynton-beach-man-escapes-current-1786999.html|archivedate=August 26, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> Localized beach erosion was also reported, although it was not significant.<ref name=\"WPTV\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wptv.com/dpp/news/tropical-storm-irene-forms-near-the-lesser-antilles|title=Scattered rain, wind gusts hit South Florida as Irene plows through Bahamas|last=Glazer|first=Glenn|date=August 25, 2011|publisher=[[WPTV-TV]]|accessdate=August 25, 2011|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61Efcxk4H?url=http://www.wptv.com/dpp/news/tropical-storm-irene-forms-near-the-lesser-antilles|archivedate=August 26, 2011|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Onshore, comparatively light winds brushed the state; the [[Lake Worth, Florida|Lake Worth]] pier reporting a peak gust of {{convert|40|mph|km/h|abbr=on}}, with the [[Palm Beach International Airport]] recording winds of no more than {{convert|31|mph|km/h|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"WPTV\"/> Precipitation in the area was also light, with a peak accumulation of {{convert|2.67|in|mm}} recorded at [[Fort Lauderdale Executive Airport]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/data/obhistory/KFXE.html|title=Weather observations for the past three days: Fort Lauderdale Executive Airport |date=August 25, 2011 |publisher=National Weather Service |accessdate=August 25, 2011 |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61D38BoUd?url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/data/obhistory/KFXE.html |archivedate=August 25, 2011}}</ref> Further north, rainfall from the storm totaled no more than {{convert|1.31|in|mm}} on August 24 in [[Melbourne, Florida|Melbourne]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wunderground.com/history/airport/KMLB/2011/8/25/DailyHistory.html?req_city=NA&req_state=NA&req_statename=NA|title=History for Melbourne, FL|date=August 26, 2011|publisher=Weather Underground|accessdate=August 27, 2011}}</ref>\n\n=====South Carolina=====\nOwing to its unusually large windfield, Irene affected long stretches of [[South Carolina]] coastlines with gusts and sporadic heavy showers, even though it remained offshore. Gale-force winds picked up through the [[South Carolina Lowcountry|Lowcountry]] during the afternoon of August 26, with a gust of {{convert|55|mph|km/h|abbr=on}} measured at a coastal marine observing site on [[Folly Island]].<ref name=powerout>{{cite web|url=http://www.postandcourier.com/news/2011/aug/26/power-out-folly/|title=Forecasters: Worst of Irene moving through Lowcountry now|first1=Bo|last1=Peterson|first2=Glenn|last2=Smith|date=August 26, 2011|accessdate=August 26, 2011|publisher=[[Evening Post Publishing Company]]|work=[[The Post and Courier]]}}</ref> Scattered power outages left over 4,000 residences in the dark, mostly due to toppled utility poles.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independentmail.com/news/2011/aug/26/rain-irene-falling-sc-coast/|title=Rain from Irene falling on S.C. coast|publisher=Independent Publishing Company|work=[[The Anderson Independent-Mail]]|date=August 26, 2011|accessdate=August 26, 2011|author=Smith, Bruce|agency=[[Associated Press]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130518174146/http://www.independentmail.com/news/2011/aug/26/rain-irene-falling-sc-coast/|archivedate=May 18, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The winds also felled trees and generated rough surf along [[Charleston County, South Carolina|Charleston County]] coastlines, and minor beach erosion was noted. Elsewhere in that county, a downed tree trapped several people in their vehicle, but they were all rescued.<ref name=powerout />\n\n=====North Carolina=====\nTropical-storm-force winds began to affect the [[Outer Banks]] hours before landfall, producing waves of {{convert|6|\u2013|9|ft|m|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"bostonglobeaug26\">{{cite news|last=Weiss|first=Mitch|title=Hurricane Irene brings rain, heavy seas to coast|url=http://www.boston.com/news/nation/articles/2011/08/26/waves_swells_from_irene_begin_hitting_nc_coast/|agency=[[Associated Press]]|work=The Boston Globe|date=August 26, 2011|accessdate=August 26, 2011}}</ref> In addition to the gales, Irene spawned several [[tornado]]es early on August 27, while approaching the coast.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/2011/al09/al092011.public_a.027.shtml|title=Hurricane Irene Intermediate Advisory Twenty-Seven A|last=Beven|first=Jack|date=August 27, 2011|publisher=[[National Hurricane Center]]|accessdate=August 27, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/2011/al09/al092011.public_b.027.shtml |title=Hurricane Irene Intermediate Advisory Twenty-Seven B|last1=Beven|first1=Jack|first2=Michael|last2=Brennan|date=August 27, 2011|publisher=[[National Hurricane Center]]|accessdate=August 27, 2011}}</ref> No regular weather station or [[Weather buoy|buoy]], however, measured sustained hurricane-force winds from the storm, with the highest winds officially recorded at {{convert|67|mph|km/h|abbr=on}} by a buoy near [[Cape Lookout, North Carolina|Cape Lookout]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wunderground.com/blog/JeffMasters/comment.html?entrynum=1906|title=Irene sends 4.5-foot storm surge up Chesapeake Bay|last=Masters|first=Jeff|date=August 28, 2011|publisher=Weather Underground|accessdate=August 28, 2011}}</ref> Precipitation totals from Irene in the region were particularly high, ranging between {{convert|10|-|14|in|mm}}; Bunyan recorded a peak amount of approximately {{convert|14|in|mm}}.<ref name=\"advis30A\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/2011/al09/al092011.public_a.030.shtml|title=Hurricane Irene Advisory Number Thirty-A|author1=Stewart, Stacy |author2=Berg, Robbie |date=August 27, 2011|publisher=[[National Hurricane Center]]|accessdate=August 27, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe large hurricane left extensive damage in its wake and produced tornadoes that damaged homes and overturned vehicles.<ref name=treeso>{{cite web|url=http://www.wsoctv.com/news/28999177/detail.html|title=Irene devastates NC coast claiming multiple lives|author=WSOC-TV|date=August 27, 2011|accessdate=August 28, 2011|publisher=[[Cox Enterprises]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/62xGwYXAv?url=http://www.wsoctv.com/news/28999177/detail.html|archivedate=November 4, 2011|df=mdy-all|author-link=WSOC-TV}}</ref> Following the touch down of a potent tornado, at least four homes were demolished in [[Columbia, North Carolina|Columbia]], while up to three others sustained significant damage.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.wnct.com/news/2011/aug/27/tornado-confirmed-tyrrell-county-ar-1336417/|title=Tornado confirmed in Tyrell County|publisher=[[Eyewitness News]]|author=WNCT|date=August 27, 2011|accessdate=August 28, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/62xJ2y7CF?url=http://www2.wnct.com/news/2011/aug/27/tornado-confirmed-tyrrell-county-ar-1336417/|archivedate=November 5, 2011|df=mdy-all|author-link=WNCT-TV}}</ref> The hurricane caused multiple flooded areas and uprooted trees along coastlines;<ref name=treeso /> in [[Nash County, North Carolina|Nash County]], a snatched tree limb struck and killed one person.<ref>{{cite news|title=Hurricane Irene batters N.C., killing 1|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/44297053|accessdate=August 27, 2011|publisher=NBC News|date=August 27, 2011}}</ref> Prior to the storm, a resident in [[Onslow County, North Carolina|Onslow County]] suffered a fatal heart attack while applying plywood to his house.<ref>{{cite news|last=Zucchino|first=David|title=Hurricane Irene: First two deaths from storm are reported|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/nationnow/2011/08/hurricane-irene-first-deaths.html|accessdate=August 27, 2011|work=Los Angeles Times|date=August 27, 2011|last2=Fausset|first2=Richard }}</ref> Two people in [[Pitt County, North Carolina|Pitt]] and [[Sampson County, North Carolina|Sampson]] Counties were additionally killed by falling trees, as were two others in [[Goldsboro, North Carolina|Goldsboro]] and Pitt County in traffic accidents. A man also drowned in the flooded [[Cape Fear River]].<ref name=\"ABC6\"/> All in all, over 1,100 homes were destroyed. The estimated $71 million in damage did not include agricultural losses.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newsobserver.com/2011/08/31/1449206/after-the-winds-and-floods-irenes.html|title=After the winds and floods, Irene's massive toll rolls in|last1=Jarvis|first1=Craig|last2=Siceloff|first2=Bruce|work=[[News & Observer]]|date=August 31, 2011|accessdate=October 27, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131006214127/http://www.newsobserver.com/2011/08/31/1449206/after-the-winds-and-floods-irenes.html|archivedate=October 6, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nHurricane Irene cut several breaches across [[North Carolina Highway 12]] on [[Hatteras Island]], isolating the island from the rest of the [[Outer Banks]]. Several of the smaller breaches were filled in with sand, but the largest, which is {{convert|200|ft|m}} wide, was left open, recreating [[Pea Island]] for the first time since 1945. As a result, the only way to access Hatteras Island was by ferry. On October 10, 2011, a temporary {{convert|662|ft|m|adj=mid|-long}} bridge opened over the breach. The bridge could be in place for more than 10 years while other solutions are considered.<ref name=hr101011>{{cite news|first=Deirdre |last= Fernandes |date= October 10, 2011 |title= N.C. 12 has opened, restoring traffic to Hatteras Island |url= http://hamptonroads.com/2011/10/nc-12-reopen-restoring-traffic-hatteras |work= [[The Virginian-Pilot]] |location= Norfolk, Virginia|accessdate=October 11, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe path of the hurricane was thought by many to be the [[scenario planning|worst-case scenario]] for the Outer Banks, just east over the [[Pamlico Sound]]. The storm winds pushed the water rushing into the sound in the form of rainfall back up the rivers feeding the sound and when the hurricane passed the water rushed back out causing historic flooding along the Outer Banks in particular in the towns of Waves, Rodanthe and Salvo. The flood caused major damage to the area that can still be seen in [https://sites.google.com/site/mirlobeachnc/hurricane-irene-damage-to-mirlo-beach Mirlo Beach] at the north end of Rodanthe. Flood waters exceeded seven feet in many locations and destroyed many houses and businesses.\n\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"150px\">\nImage:Irene radar 20110827 1154 UTC.gif|Radar image of the storm at landfall in the Outer Banks of North Carolina.\nImage:Hurricane Irene landfall NASA.jpg|Irene over North Carolina on August 27.\nFile:Hurricane Irene Hits the US.ogv|The astronauts on board the ISS captured this series of still frames as Hurricane Irene, a category 1 storm at the time, made landfall into the coast of North Carolina.\n</gallery>\n\n=====Virginia=====\n[[File:Flooded boardwalk near Toms Cove Visitor Center (6094141162).jpg|thumb|right|Flooding at [[Chincoteague National Wildlife Refuge]] on [[Assateague Island]]]]\nA tornado moved through the [[Sandbridge, Virginia Beach, Virginia|Sandbridge]] community in [[Virginia Beach]], in the morning hours of August 27, ripping the roofs off at least five homes and damaging several others.<ref>{{cite news |last=Hixenbaugh|first=Mike|title=Tornado rips through Sandbridge, damages homes|url=http://hamptonroads.com/2011/08/tornado-rips-through-sandbridge-damages-homes|work=The Virginian-Pilot|accessdate=August 27, 2011|date=August 27, 2011}}</ref> High winds in [[Newport News, Virginia|Newport News]] knocked a tree into an apartment complex.<ref name=\"6VA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/44297053|title=Six dead as Hurricane Irene edges into Virginia|date=August 27, 2011|publisher=NBC News|accessdate=August 27, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.dailypress.com/2011-08-28/news/dp-nws-child-death-folo-0829-20110828_1_apartment-building-tree-prayer-group|title=Mother took spot close to window before son killed by crashing tree|last=Dujardin|first=Peter|date=August 28, 2011|publisher=[[Daily Press (Virginia)|Daily Press]]|accessdate=November 1, 2011}}</ref> Three other Virginians in [[Brunswick County, Virginia|Brunswick]], [[Chesterfield County, Virginia|Chesterfield]] and [[King William County, Virginia|King William]] Counties were also killed by falling trees.<ref name=\"ABC6\"/> Most severe damage consisted of many downed trees on power lines, cars, homes, and roads; and flooding in many low-lying roads and neighborhoods \u2013 1.2 million homes and businesses lost power due to Irene.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailypress.com/news/weather/stormguide/dp-nws-irene-outages-tuesday-20110829,0,737042.story|title=UPDATE: 155,000 in Hampton Roads still without power|authors=Lessig, Hugh; Frost, Peter|date=August 30, 2011|publisher=Daily Press|accessdate=November 1, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120119052740/http://www.dailypress.com/news/weather/stormguide/dp-nws-irene-outages-tuesday-20110829,0,737042.story|archive-date=January 19, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n====Mid-Atlantic states====\nHurricane Irene caused widespread power outages in Delaware, Maryland, New Jersey, Pennsylvania, and Washington, D.C.<ref name=kywpower>{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.cbslocal.com/2011/08/28/hurricane-irene-power-outages/|title=Hurricane Irene: Power Outages|date=August 28, 2011|publisher=[[KYW-TV]]|location=Philadelphia|accessdate=September 6, 2011}}{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wmdt.com/story/15350162/about-500000-customers-in-mid-atlantic-lack-power|title=About 500,000 customers in mid-Atlantic lack power|date=August 29, 2011|publisher=[[WMDT-TV]]|location=Salisbury, Maryland|accessdate=September 6, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140116232318/http://www.wmdt.com/story/15350162/about-500000-customers-in-mid-atlantic-lack-power|archivedate=January 16, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wboc.com/story/15347354/more-than-71000-lose-power-in-mid-atlantic|title=Nearly 1 Million Lose Power in Mid-Atlantic|date=August 28, 2011|publisher=[[WBOC-TV|WBOC]]|location=Salisbury, Maryland|accessdate=September 6, 2011}}</ref>\n\n=====Maryland=====\n[[File:Fallen tree in Washington D.C. after Hurricane Irene.JPG|thumb|right|A [[Lexus RX (XU30)#MHU33 / MHU38 (2005, 2006)|Lexus RX450h]] damaged by a fallen tree in Washington, D.C.]]\nDorchester General Hospital in [[Cambridge, Maryland|Cambridge]] was evacuated after there was wind and water damage<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.poweredbythepeople.com/water_damage/MD.php|title=The Water Damage Restoration project in Maryland|publisher=The Water restoration group in MD| date=2011-12-02}}</ref> to the laboratory roof.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wboc.com/story/15347428/irene-damage-forces-md-hospital-evacuation|title=Irene Damage Forces Md. Hospital Evacuation|date=August 28, 2011|publisher=[[WBOC-TV|WBOC]]|location=Salisbury, Maryland|accessdate=September 6, 2011}}</ref> In [[Queen Anne's County, Maryland]], an 85-year-old woman was killed when a tree fell onto her house causing the chimney to collapse.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/post_now/post/hurricane-irene-aftermath-dispatches-from-virginia-marland-delaware-and-the-district/2011/08/28/gIQArS2gkJ_blog.html|title=Hurricane Irene aftermath: Dispatches from Virginia, Maryland, Delaware and the District|last=Rosenthal|first=Brian|date=August 28, 2011|work=The Washington Post|accessdate=September 6, 2011}}</ref> Farm fields on the [[Eastern Shore of Maryland]] were saturated with water after the storm, causing farmers to hand-pick their crops. Some tomato, corn, and cantaloupe crops were destroyed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wmdt.com/story/15355690/hurricane-irene-takes-a-toll-on-maryland-crop|title=Hurricane Irene Takes A Toll On Maryland Crops|date=August 30, 2011|publisher=[[WMDT-TV]]|location=Salisbury, Maryland|accessdate=September 6, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928073718/http://www.wmdt.com/story/15355690/hurricane-irene-takes-a-toll-on-maryland-crop|archive-date=September 28, 2011|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n=====Delaware=====\n\nTwo 25-year-old men were killed in the [[Hockessin, Delaware|Hockessin]] area in an apparent drowning after attempting to run home through the storm on Saturday night. Their bodies were recovered near [[Wilmington, Delaware|Wilmington]] on Monday afternoon.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.delawareonline.com/article/20110829/NEWS/110829020/Bodies-missing-men-found?odyssey=mod|title=Bodies of missing men found|author=The News Journal|date=August 29, 2011|publisher=DelawareOnline|accessdate=September 6, 2011|author-link=The News Journal}}</ref> An EF1 tornado touched down in [[Lewes, Delaware|Lewes]], at 6:38&nbsp;pm, causing a path of destruction 80 yards wide and 3/4 of a mile long, damaging about 50 homes and destroying one.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.delmarvanow.com/article/20110831/NEWS01/110831026/IRENE-NWS-says-tornado-hit-near-Lewes-95-mph-winds?odyssey=tab|title=IRENE: NWS says tornado hit near Lewes with 95 mph winds|date=August 31, 2011|publisher=DelmarvaNow.com|location=Salisbury, Maryland|accessdate=September 6, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923213503/http://www.delmarvanow.com/article/20110831/NEWS01/110831026/IRENE-NWS-says-tornado-hit-near-Lewes-95-mph-winds?odyssey=tab|archive-date=September 23, 2015|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Heavy rains throughout the state were topped at {{convert|10.43|in|mm}} in [[Ellendale, Delaware|Ellendale]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.delawareonline.com/article/20110829/NEWS/110829002/Updated-rainfall-totals?odyssey=mod|title=Updated rainfall totals|author=The News Journal|date=August 29, 2011|publisher=DelawareOnline|accessdate=September 6, 2011}}</ref> Flooding occurred in many areas including the [[Delaware Bay]] communities of [[Slaughter Beach, Delaware|Slaughter Beach]], [[Primehook Beach, Delaware|Primehook Beach]], and [[Broadkill Beach, Delaware|Broadkill Beach]]. Sections of Prime Hook Road leading to Primehook Beach were washed out. Irene flooded and forced the closure of [[Delaware Route 1]] near the [[Indian River Inlet Bridge]], pushing sand onto the road.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sussex County Assesses Damage in Wake of Irene|publisher=WBOC-TV|location=Salisbury, MD|date=August 28, 2011|url=http://www.wboc.com/story/15347250/sussex-county-assesses-damage-in-wake-of-irene|accessdate=September 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=====Pennsylvania=====\n[[File:Hurricane Irene downed branch Kutztown PA.jpg|thumb|right|A downed tree branch in [[Kutztown, Pennsylvania]]]]\nFive people were killed in [[Pennsylvania]]: three died as a result of fallen trees, one was killed in a traffic accident, and a woman was swept away by flooding in the [[Wissahickon Creek]].<ref name=\"ABC6\"/> In [[Philadelphia]], the storm left thousands without power. More than 400 trees fell in Philadelphia, and 200 trees fell in Pittsburgh, seven buildings collapsed and twenty roads were closed. [[PECO Energy Company|PECO]] worked on restoring power by mid-week.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.com/articles/205337/20110829/hurricane-irene-philadelphia-flooding.htm|title=Hurricane Irene Philadelphia: Hundreds of Thousands Without Power|date=August 29, 2011|work=[[International Business Times]] |accessdate=September 6, 2011}}</ref>\n\n=====New Jersey=====\n{{main|Effects of Hurricane Irene in New Jersey}}\n[[File:Raritan River Flood, New Brunswick, NJ.JPG|thumb|right|The Raritan River at New Brunswick on August&nbsp;29, 2011, one day after Hurricane Irene landfall]]\nWhile the storm made landfall next to [[Galloway Township, New Jersey|Galloway]] and [[Little Egg Harbor Township, New Jersey|Little Egg Harbor]] in the southeastern part of the state, [[South Jersey]] received little damage and flooding.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.app.com/article/20110830/NJNEWS/308300008/Town-near-Irene-s-eye-eludes-disaster |title=Town near Irene's eye eludes disaster |work=Asbury Park Press |author=Scully, Paula |date=30 August 2011 |accessdate=September 1, 2011}}</ref> Further north, severe river flooding occurred<ref>{{cite web|last=Sterling|first=Steven|title=Hurricane Irene leads to historic flooding after month's record rainfall|url=http://www.nj.com/news/index.ssf/2011/08/hurricane_irene_causes_histori.html|accessdate=August 29, 2011|work=[[The Star-Ledger]]|publisher=NJ.com}}</ref> due to record rainfall,<ref>{{cite web|last=Hutchins|first=Ryan|title=Fairfield closed off to non-residents after Passaic River overflows into township|url=http://www.nj.com/news/index.ssf/2011/08/flooding_passaic_river_shuts_d.html|accessdate=August 29, 2011|work=[[The Star-Ledger]]|publisher=NJ.com}}</ref> with a statewide rainfall maxima of {{convert|11.27|in|mm}} in [[Freehold Township, New Jersey|Freehold]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Sterling|first=Steven|title=N.J. rainfall map \u2013 storm totals from Hurricane Irene|url=http://www.nj.com/weather-guy/index.ssf/2011/08/nj_rainfall_map_-_storm_totals.html|accessdate=August 29, 2011|work=[[The Star-Ledger]]|publisher=NJ.com}}</ref> Eleven rivers reached record levels, and a week after the storm all rivers in the state remained at \"moderate flooding level\".<ref name = mudflood>{{Citation |last = Baker |first = Al |title = Amid Mud and Floods, Push to Restore Power |newspaper = The New York Times |date = September 3, 2011 |url = https://www.nytimes.com/2011/09/04/nyregion/after-tropical-storm-irene-push-to-restore-power-in-new-york-region.html?_r=1&ref=nyregion |accessdate=September 3, 2011}}</ref> The flooding affected roads, including the heavily used [[Interstate 287#Morris County|Interstate 287]] and [[Garden State Parkway]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Frassinelli|first=Mike|title=Hurricane Irene wreaks havoc on New Jersey highways|url=http://www.nj.com/news/index.ssf/2011/08/hurricane_irene_wreaks_havoc_o.html|accessdate=August 20, 2011|work=[[The Star-Ledger]]|publisher=NJ.com}}</ref> Along the [[Hudson River]], floodwaters affected parts of [[Jersey City, New Jersey|Jersey City]]<ref>{{Cite news | last = Krudy | first = Edward Krudy | title = Jersey City, a satellite for Wall St, hit by floods |agency=Reuters | date = August 28, 2011 | url = https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/08/28/us-storm-irene-jerseycity-idUSTRE77R3B620110828 |accessdate=September 15, 2011}}</ref> and [[Hoboken, New Jersey|Hoboken]].<ref>{{Citation |last=Colanari |first=Katie |title=Amphibious truck delivering supplies to southwest Hoboken where flood waters are up to 5 feet deep |newspaper=The Jersey Journal |date=August 28, 2011 |url=http://www.nj.com/hobokennow/index.ssf/2011/08/amphibious_truck_delivering_su.html |accessdate=September 15, 2011}}</ref> The north tube of the [[Holland Tunnel]] was briefly closed.<ref name = holland>{{Cite press release |title =PORT AUTHORITY REOPENS NORTH TUBE OF THE HOLLAND TUNNEL | publisher = Port Authority of New York and New Jersey |date=August 28, 2011 |url=http://www.panynj.gov/press-room/press-item.cfm?headLine_id=1457 |accessdate=February 14, 2014}}</ref> Flooding affected the train lines in the Trenton area.<ref>{{cite news |last=Karas |first=David |title=Flooding from Hurricane Irene inundates tracks at Trenton Transit Center (with video) |url=http://www.nj.com/mercer/index.ssf/2011/08/trenton_transit_center_floods.html |accessdate=August 29, 2011 |newspaper=The Times of Trenton - NJ.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Rouse |first=Karen |title=Hurricane Irene cost NJ Transit $10 million, official says |newspaper=The Record |date=September 14, 2011 |url=http://www.northjersey.com/news/transportation/NJ_Transit_meeting_focuses_on_storm_performance.html |accessdate=September 16, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120623084539/http://www.northjersey.com/news/transportation/NJ_Transit_meeting_focuses_on_storm_performance.html |archivedate=June 23, 2012 |df=mdy-all}}</ref> The storm killed seven people in the state,<ref name=\"tcr\"/> and damage was estimated at around $1&nbsp;billion.<ref>{{cite web|author=National Climatic Data Center|year=2011|title=Event Report for New Jersey|accessdate=February 18, 2012|url=http://www4.ncdc.noaa.gov/cgi-win/wwcgi.dll?wwevent~ShowEvent~893943}}{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn addition to major flooding, the combination of already heavily saturated ground from a wet summer, and heavy wind gusts made New Jersey especially vulnerable to wind damage, notably in [[Union County, New Jersey|Union County]]. Fallen trees blocked vital roads, including portions of [[New Jersey Route 28]] and [[U.S. Route 22]]. Numerous homes suffered structural damages from the wind.{{Citation needed|date=September 2011}} In total, approximately 1.46 million customers of [[JCP&L]] and [[Public Service Enterprise Group|PSEG]] throughout most of the 21 counties lost power.<ref name = powercompany>{{Citation | last = Spoto |first = MaryAnn |last2 = Considine |first2 = Bob |title = Gov. Chris Christie bears down on power companies to relight rest of N.J. |newspaper = The Star Ledger |date = September 2, 2011 |url = http://www.nj.com/news/index.ssf/2011/09/post_236.html |accessdate=September 3, 2011 |quote = Some 560,000 JCP&L customers lost power from the storm. Power had been restored by yesterday to all but 750 of the approximately 800,000 PSE&G customers affected by Irene.}}</ref> On Sunday September 5, power had been returned to last remaining 2,000 residents who suffered a [[power outage]].<ref>{{Citation |title = All NJ residents affected by Irene have power back |newspaper = Asbury Park Press |date = September 5, 2011 |url = http://www.app.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=2011309050034 |accessdate=September 6, 2011}}</ref>\n\nFlooding in some parts of the state continued for another three days.<ref>{{cite news | last = Grynbaum | first = Michael | title = Water Still Rises in New Jersey and Connecticut | newspaper = The New York Times | date = August 30, 2011 | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2011/08/31/nyregion/water-continues-to-rise-in-new-jersey-and-connecticut.html |accessdate=August 31, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last = Star Ledger Staff | title = 3 days after Hurricane Irene hits, floodwaters continue to destroy homes, close roads | newspaper = [[The Star-Ledger]] | date = August 30, 2011 | url = http://www.nj.com/news/index.ssf/2011/08/3_days_after_hurricane_irene_h.html |accessdate=August 31, 2011}}</ref> On August 31, [[Paterson, New Jersey|Paterson]] counted 6,000 displaced persons, and three of four bridges crossing the [[Passaic River]] remained closed.<ref>{{Citation |last = Dolnick |first = Sam |title = River, at 100-Year High, Ravages a City That Once Thrived on It |newspaper = The New York Times |date = September 1, 2011 |url = https://www.nytimes.com/2011/09/01/nyregion/paterson-nj-is-devastated-by-floods-after-hurricane-irene.html?_r=1&ref=nyregion |accessdate=September 9, 2011}}</ref> On August&nbsp;31, President [[Barack Obama]] declared the state a [[disaster area]],<ref name=\"disaster area\">{{Citation |title = President Obama declares N.J. a disaster area as residents continue to deal with Hurricane Irene's impact |newspaper = The Star-Ledger |date = September 1, 2011 |url = http://www.nj.com/news/index.ssf/2011/09/president_obama_declares_nj_a.html |accessdate=September 1, 2011}}</ref> including all [[List of counties in New Jersey|21 counties]].<ref>{{Citation |title = All 21 New Jersey counties to receive FEMA aid for Hurricane Irene recovery |newspaper = The Jersey Journal |date = September 6, 2011 |url = http://www.nj.com/hudson/index.ssf/2011/09/all_21_new_jersey_counties_to.html |accessdate=September 6, 2011}}</ref> More than 31,000 residents filed assistance claims through FEMA, and within two weeks nearly $38 million had been disbursed with others pending. Hardest-hit counties were [[Bergen County|Bergen]] and [[Passaic County|Passaic]] in the [[Gateway Region|northeast]], each with more than 4,000 claims.<ref>{{Citation |last = Goldberg |first = Dan |title = Bill to provide Hurricane Irene relief fails in U.S. Senate |newspaper = The Star-Ledger |date=September 12, 2011 |url=http://www.nj.com/news/index.ssf/2011/09/bill_to_provide_hurricane_iren.html |accessdate=September 13, 2011}}</ref>\n\nDespite the mandatory evacuations ordered for many parts of the Jersey Shore, the damage and flooding in that area of the state was not as severe as predicted. This miscalculation was met with frustration among many coastal residents that were evacuated out of an abundance of caution. A year later, when evacuations were ordered for [[Hurricane Sandy]], some residents were reluctant or skeptical about the storm's potential and their preparations were more lax, since some of Irene's impacts fell short of the original predictions. This proved very damaging for some, as Hurricane Sandy ended up being far worse than predicted.\n\n=====New York=====\n{{main|Effects of Hurricane Irene in New York}}\nIn [[Manhattan]], the [[Hudson River]] flooded in the [[Meatpacking District]].<ref name = holland/> [[Long Beach, New York|Long Beach]] and [[Freeport, New York|Freeport]], both of which experienced serious flooding, were among the worst-hit towns on Long Island,<ref name=\"Long Island\">{{cite news |last=Benkoe |first=Jeff |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/08/28/us-storm-irene-longisland-idUSTRE77R2FG20110828|title=Long Island pounded by Irene but residents feel lucky|agency=Reuters|date=August 28, 2011|accessdate=September 14, 2011}}</ref> and many roads were left impassable. The workers at [[Ground Zero]] in Lower Manhattan worked to make the World Trade Center site hurricane proof, and escaped major damage, just missing the tenth anniversary of 9/11.<ref name=\"Long Island\"/>\n\nThe winds knocked down many trees and power lines, leaving almost 350,000 homes and businesses without power in [[Nassau County, New York|Nassau]] and [[Suffolk County, New York|Suffolk]] counties.<ref>Jonathan Allen \u2013 [https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/08/29/us-storm-irene-longisland-idUSTRE77S6MU20110829 \"Long Island residents frustrated by power outages\"] \u2013 Reuters \u2013 August 29, 2011 \u2013 Retrieved August 30, 2011.</ref>\n\nFlooding of the [[Ramapo River]] and more than a half-mile (1&nbsp;km) of washouts led both Metro-North and [[New Jersey Transit Rail Operations|NJ Transit]] to suspend service on the [[Port Jervis Line]] north of [[Suffern (NJT station)|Suffern]] for nearly three months.<ref name=\"Port Jervis Line suspension\">{{cite web|title=NJ TRANSIT Service Information for Tuesday, August 30|url=http://www.njtransit.com/sa/sa_servlet.srv?hdnPageAction=ServiceAdjustmentTo&AdjustmentId=7954|publisher=NJ Transit|date=August 29, 2011|accessdate=September 14, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.myfoxny.com/dpp/news/metro-north-port-jervis-line-set-to-resume-service-20111123|title=Metro North Port Jervis Line Set to Resume Service|first=Robert|last=Moses|date=November 23, 2011|accessdate=November 24, 2011}}</ref>\n\nFlooding overwhelmed several [[sewage treatment]] plants, since many of them collect and processed storm [[Surface runoff|runoff]] as well as [[wastewater]]. At least 52 municipalities in the [[Hudson Valley]] reported raw-sewage spills into local waters.<ref name=\"THR sewage failures story\">{{cite news|last=Bosch|first=Adam|title=Sewage plants no match for Irene, authorities say|url=http://www.recordonline.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20110908/NEWS/109080314/-1/NEWS|newspaper=Times-Herald Record|date=September 8, 2011|accessdate=September 14, 2011}}</ref> Vaccinations against [[tetanus]] and [[hepatitis]] were offered to rescuers before entering houses in some areas.<ref name=\"THR Goshen sewage story\">{{cite news|last=Sullivan|first=John|title=Raw sewage worried rescuers in Goshen |url=http://www.recordonline.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20110908/NEWS/109080313/-1/NEWS |newspaper=Times-Herald Record|date=September 8, 2011 |accessdate=February 14, 2014}}</ref> Parts of [[Washingtonville, New York|Washingtonville]] were under {{convert|8|ft|m}} of water during the storm due to the flash flood of [[Moodna Creek]], wrecking some nearby homes.<ref name=\"THR Washingtonville story\">{{cite news|last=Sullivan|first=John|title=Hundreds in Washingtonville displaced by Irene|url=http://www.recordonline.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20110902/NEWS/109020348|newspaper=Times-Herald Record|date=September 2, 2011|accessdate=September 14, 2011}}</ref>\n\nDisastrous flash floods occurred in the northwestern [[Catskill Mountains]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Kinsman|first=Kat|title=Amid devastating New York flooding, a stream of information|url=http://www.cnn.com/2011/TECH/social.media/08/29/new.york.irene.reports/|accessdate=August 29, 2011 |newspaper=Cable Network News|date=September 14, 2011}}</ref> Record flooding along the [[Schoharie Creek]] destroyed the 156-year-old [[Old Blenheim Bridge]], a [[National Historic Landmark]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Covered Bridges, Beloved Remnants of Another Era, Were Casualties, Too |first=Erik |last=Eckholm |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/09/01/us/01bridges.html|newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=August 31, 2011 |accessdate=September 14, 2011}}</ref>\n\nFlooding by [[Schoharie Creek]] in the town of [[Prattsville, NY]] caused major damage and destroyed large areas of the town. Every structure on the strip that comprises Main Street was partly or fully destroyed, including all 22 of the town's businesses. Eleven houses collapsed in the flood, fifteen were condemned and torn down, and more than 100 homes were so damaged that the residents couldn't return to them, but amazingly there were zero fatalities.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news| last=Dean| first=Josh| title=Please God Stop the Rain| url=http://nymag.com/print/?/news/features/prattsville-hurricane-irene-2012-8/| newspaper=New York Magazine| date=August 19, 2012}}</ref> It received widespread national news coverage because the town had nearly been washed away.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.timesunion.com/default/photo/Hylan-Boulevard-in-Prattsville-just-down-from-1567493.php |title=Photo of Hylan Boulevard in Prattsville |publisher=Times Union |date=2011-09-01 |accessdate=2012-09-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.timesunion.com/default/photo/Across-Main-Street-from-the-Morses-in-1567495.php |title=Photo of across Main Street from the Morses |publisher=Times Union |date=2011-09-01 |accessdate=2012-09-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Vielkind |first=Jimmy |url=http://www.timesunion.com/default/article/We-thought-we-were-going-to-die-2150370.php |title=We thought we were going to die |publisher=Times Union |date=September 1, 2011 |accessdate=2012-09-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Waldman |first=Scott |url=http://www.timesunion.com/local/article/Survival-is-town-s-greatest-test-2163960.php |title=Survival is town's greatest test |publisher=Times Union |date=September 10, 2011 |accessdate=2012-09-14}}</ref> Gov. Andrew M. Cuomo labeled Prattsville as the place in New York State hardest hit by the storm.<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2012/08/27/nyregion/a-year-after-tropical-storm-irene-hope-and-uncertainty-in-prattsville-ny.html?pagewanted=all</ref>\nLocal officials estimated that approximately one-third of all the houses and businesses in the village of Schoharie had been destroyed due to flooding. The Gilboa Dam, built in 1926, which had undergone some strengthening procedures during 2005 and 2006, sustained minor damage due to the flooding of the Schoharie Creek.\n\nFurther upstate, Irene did significant damage in the [[Adirondack Mountains]]. A section of [[New York State Route 73|NY 73]] was washed out, isolating two hamlets.<ref name=\"NYT Keene story\">{{cite news|last=Rubin|first=Alissa J.|authorlink= Alissa J. Rubin |title=In the Adirondacks, Storm-Battered and Cut Off|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/09/01/nyregion/tropical-storm-irene-leaves-keene-in-adirondacks-battered-and-cut-off.html|accessdate=September 14, 2011|newspaper=The New York Times|date=August 31, 2011}}</ref> DEC reported that \"[[landslide]]s too numerous to count\" had taken place on many of the High Peaks themselves, all of which are located on state [[Forest Preserve (New York)|Forest Preserve]] land.<ref name=\"DEC ADK closures\">{{cite web|title=Adirondack Trail Information|url=http://www.dec.ny.gov/outdoor/7865.html|publisher=[[New York State Department of Environmental Conservation]]|accessdate=September 14, 2011}}</ref> Overall, there were ten deaths in the state, most due to flooding.<ref name=\"tcr\"/>\n\nOn September 3, Governor Cuomo announced the creation of a $15 million federal relief fund to help farmers there cope with the damage,<ref name=\"NYT Saturday power story\">{{cite news|last=Baker|first=Al|title=Amid Mud and Floods, Push to Restore Power|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/09/04/nyregion/after-tropical-storm-irene-push-to-restore-power-in-new-york-region.html|newspaper=The New York Times|date=September 3, 2011|accessdate=September 14, 2011}}</ref> after an estimated $45 million in crop damage on {{convert|145000|acre}}.<ref name=\"THR farmers story\">{{cite news|last=Sunkin |first=Alyssa |title=Acres of crops got washed away |url=http://www.recordonline.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20110904/NEWS/109040314 |newspaper=Times-Herald Record |date=September 4, 2011 |accessdate=February 14, 2014}}</ref> In mid-September, farmers reported a smaller-than-average harvest of pumpkins in the northeastern United States.<ref name=\"pumpkinshortage\">{{cite news|last=Gibson|first=Megan|date=September 20, 2011|title=The Great Pumpkin Shortage: Stormy Summer Limits Supply In Northeast|url=http://newsfeed.time.com/2011/09/20/the-great-pumpkin-shortage-stormy-summer-limits-supply-in-northeast/|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|accessdate=February 18, 2012}}</ref> By that point, many farmers in the Black Dirt Region were near bankruptcy, and fundraisers were being held to tide them over pending federal disaster relief.<ref name=\"Warwick Farm Aid\">{{cite web|title=Warwick Farm Aid Sept. 25, 2011|url=http://www.warwickfarmaid.com/|year=2011|accessdate=September 19, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110924053911/http://www.warwickfarmaid.com/|archive-date=September 24, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> Farmers were worried the reports would deter tourists from [[Agritourism#Agritourism in the United States|visiting farm country]] for traditional autumn activities and purchases, an economic setback which some said would exacerbate the damage from the storm.<ref name=\"THR September farm damage story\">{{cite news|last=Horrigan|first=Jeremiah|title=Farmers despairing over monumental losses of crops|url=http://www.recordonline.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20110919/NEWS/109190329/-1/NEWS|newspaper=Times-Herald Record|date=September 19, 2011|accessdate=September 19, 2011}}</ref> Many planned to remain open and offer what they could to visitors.<ref name=\"THR agritourism story\">{{cite news|last=Horrigan|first=Jeremiah|title=Not all farmers done in by floods|url=http://www.recordonline.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20110919/NEWS/109190327/-1/NEWS|newspaper=Times-Herald Record|date=September 19, 2011|accessdate=September 19, 2011}}</ref>\n\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"150px\">\nFile:Hurricane Irene flooding of Mill Dam Bridge in Centerport, New York.jpg|Storm surge flooding in [[Centerport, New York]] as the eye of Irene passed near high tide.\nFile:Port Jervis Line tracks damaged by flooding, Sloatsburg, NY.jpg|alt=Two sets of railroad tracks twisted and tilted, with some woody debris on and around them|Damage to the [[Port Jervis Line]]\nFile:Forge Hill Road bridge washout after Hurricane Irene, New Windsor, NY.jpg|A road washout in [[New Windsor, New York|New Windsor]]\n</gallery>\n\n====New England====\n\n=====Connecticut=====\n[[File:Hurricane Irene Storm Surge in Greenwich, CT.JPG|thumb|right|[[Storm surge]] from Hurricane Irene in [[Greenwich, Connecticut]]]]\nIn [[Connecticut]], 20 homes in [[East Haven, Connecticut|East Haven]] were destroyed and five others were damaged beyond repair by flooding and storm surge along the shore of [[Long Island Sound]].<ref name=\"CT\">[https://archive.today/20130119234650/http://www.courant.com/news/weather/hurricane/hc-hurricane-irene-0829-20110828,0,3492814.story?page=1 \"754,000 Homes Without Power, Flooding Concerns Rise In Irene's Wake\"], ''The Hartford Courant'', August 28, 2011.</ref> On Sunday, Connecticut's two main electric companies, Connecticut Light and Power and [[United Illuminating]], reported that a record 754,000 customers, about half the state, were without power. More than two days after the storm made landfall, about 400,000 people were still without power, some being told they would have to wait more than a week, especially in heavily wooded areas. In [[Ridgefield, Connecticut|Ridgefield]], 90% of houses lost power, requiring the utility to turn off power to the other 10% to ease restoration efforts.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2011/09/01/nyregion/days-after-the-storm-many-are-left-in-the-dark.html?scp=6&sq=irene%20connecticut&st=cse Days After the Storm, Many Are Still in The Dark, NY Times, August 31, 2011]</ref><ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2011/08/31/nyregion/water-continues-to-rise-in-new-jersey-and-connecticut.html?_r=1&scp=1&sq=irene%20connecticut&st=cse Water Still Rises in New Jersey and Connecticut, NY Times, August 31, 2011]</ref> [[Connecticut Route 15|Route 15]], one of the state's main highways, was closed from the New York state line to [[Interstate 91 in Connecticut|Interstate 91]] in [[Meriden, Connecticut|Meriden]] due to fallen trees.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.wtnh.com/dpp/weather/severe_weather/irene-sunday-connecticut |title=Irene knocks out power, downs trees on approach |publisher=WTNH-TV |date=August 28, 2011 |accessdate=September 1, 2011 |archivedate=September 18, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110918065606/http://www.wtnh.com/dpp/weather/severe_weather/irene-sunday-connecticut |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nGovernor [[Dannel Malloy]] said Hurricane Irene was responsible for a tenth death on August 28: a man who died in a fire likely caused by downed wires from high winds.<ref>{{cite news|title=Hurricane Irene: Connecticut governor confirms 10th death|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/nationnow/2011/08/hurricane-irene-connecticut-governor-confirms-10th-death.html|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=September 14, 2011|date=August 28, 2011}}</ref> An elderly woman, who resided in [[Prospect, Connecticut|Prospect]], died in similar situations, when a falling tree caused power lines to collapse onto her home, starting a fire;<ref name=\"ABC6\"/> her husband was critically injured.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hurricane Irene: Connecticut sizes up the damage from Irene|url=http://abclocal.go.com/wabc/story?section=weather&id=8326209|work=abclocal.go.com/wabc/|publisher=ABC News|accessdate=September 14, 2011}}{{Dead link|date=April 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> In [[Bristol, Connecticut|Bristol]], a man drowned when his canoe capsized.<ref name=\"ABC6\"/>\n\nA week later, many homes in Connecticut still had not had their power restored. [[Connecticut Light & Power]] said on September 2 that it was ahead of where it expected to be, and that less than 100,000 customers would still be without power by midnight the next day. Crews had come from many distant places in North America, including [[British Columbia]], to help the utility's own crews.<ref name=\"NYT Saturday power story\" /> The continued outages also meant that in rural areas with private wells, residents still lacked running water a week after the storm.<ref name=\"NYT CT water story\">{{cite news|last=Secret|first=Mosi|title=Nearly Week Later, Thousands in Region Still Lack Clean Water|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/09/03/nyregion/several-areas-hit-by-irene-still-lack-clean-water.html|newspaper=The New York Times|date=September 2, 2011|accessdate=September 14, 2011}}</ref>\n\n=====Massachusetts=====\nIn [[Massachusetts]], damage was greatest in the [[Western Massachusetts#The Hill Towns|Hill Towns]] and [[Western Massachusetts]] as the eye of the storm tracked westward, toward Albany, New York.{{citation needed|date=September 2011}} High winds toppled trees and heavy rain caused widespread flooding of Connecticut River tributaries. The [[Westfield River]] rose almost twenty feet in a matter of hours; the [[Deerfield River]] rose over fifteen feet in the same period. Both rivers reached flood stages not seen since the 1955, and 1938, hurricanes and floods.<ref>Bent, G.C., L. Medalie, and M.G. Nielsen. (2013). [https://purl.fdlp.gov/GPO/gpo41718 High-Water Marks from Tropical Storm Irene for Selected River Reaches in Northwestern Massachusetts, August 2011.] Reston, Va.: [[United States Department of the Interior|U.S. Department of the Interior]], [[United States Geological Survey|U.S. Geological Survey]].</ref> A 6-mile stretch of [[Massachusetts Route 2|Route 2]] from Charlemont to Florida along the Cold River branch of the Deerfield was closed due to damage for over 3 months.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Daniels|first1=Tammy|title=Hurricane-Damaged Route 2 Reopens to Traffic|url=http://www.iberkshires.com/story/40079/Hurricane-Damaged-Route-2-Reopens-to-Traffic.html?source=top_stories|publisher=iBerkshires.com|accessdate=6 October 2014|date=December 15, 2011}}</ref>\n\nA [[public works]] employee was electrocuted by downed power lines in [[Southbridge, Massachusetts|Southbridge]].<ref name=\"ABC6\"/>\n\nA dam failure was mistakenly reported in [[Becket, Massachusetts|East Becket]], yet 200 people were evacuated as a precaution.<ref>{{cite news|title=Huntington Chief: Becket dam didn't fail|url=http://www.wwlp.com/dpp/news/local/berkshire/Reported-dam-failure-in-East-Becket|accessdate=September 14, 2011|publisher=WWLP|date=August 28, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121115181755/http://www.wwlp.com/dpp/news/local/berkshire/Reported-dam-failure-in-East-Becket|archivedate=November 15, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"150px\">\nFile:Hurricane Irene - Lynn Beach.jpg|Sailboats broke from their moorings and washed ashore in Massachusetts\nFile:Irene Two Broken Trees.jpg|Two trees toppled by Irene in coastal Massachusetts.\n</gallery>\n\n=====Rhode Island=====\n[[Rhode Island]] had gusts of wind up to {{convert|71|mph|km/h|abbr=on}},<ref>{{cite news|title=Irene delivers glancing blow to R.I.|url=http://www.projo.com/news/content/IRENE_29_08-29-11_IRQ15QR_v23.3e6b2.html}}</ref> uprooting trees and causing extensive damage to its power grid. By the storm's end, an estimated 256,000 out of 480,281 customers were without power.<ref>{{cite news|title=Irene leaves up to half of Rhode Island without power|url=https://www.usatoday.com/weather/storms/hurricanes/story/2011-08-28/Irene-pounds-Rhode-Island-155000-without-power/50162892/1?csp=hf| work=USA Today | date=August 28, 2011}}</ref> Rhode Island electric company, [[National Grid USA|National Grid]], expected it would take until Labor Day weekend to restore power to the most remote areas and areas which were most damaged. On August 30, two days after the storm, 138,000 customers remained without power.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.pbn.com/Utilities-push-to-restore-power-after-brush-with-Hurricane-Irene-,60837|title=Utilities push to restore power after brush with Hurricane Irene|date=August 30, 2011|access-date=August 30, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120111091032/http://www.pbn.com/Utilities-push-to-restore-power-after-brush-with-Hurricane-Irene-,60837|archive-date=January 11, 2012|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> A power line on [[Aquidneck Island]] near [[Portsmouth, Rhode Island|Portsmouth]] was felled by winds during the morning of August 28, severing power to Portsmouth, [[Middletown, Rhode Island|Middletown]], [[Newport, Rhode Island|Newport]] and [[Jamestown, Rhode Island|Jamestown]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Aerial tour of Aquidneck Island outages|url=http://www.wpri.com/dpp/weather/hurricane/gov-takes-aerial-tour-of-storm-damage|work=[[WPRI]]|date=August 28, 2011|access-date=September 17, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120405134240/http://www.wpri.com/dpp/weather/hurricane/gov-takes-aerial-tour-of-storm-damage|archive-date=April 5, 2012|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Power was not fully restored to Aquidneck Island and [[Conanicut Island]] communities until August 30. The storm surge into Narragansett Bay caused some coastal damage, although [[Providence, Rhode Island|Providence]], at the head of the bay, was spared downtown flooding in part due to its [[Fox Point Hurricane Barrier|hurricane barrier]]. There was some localized river flooding,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.projo.com/news/content/IRENE_30_08-30-11_3QQ1QD4_v26.430d9.html,60837 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120119065453/http://www.projo.com/news/content/IRENE_30_08-30-11_3QQ1QD4_v26.430d9.html,60837 |url-status=dead |archive-date=January 19, 2012 |title=Hurricane Irene }}</ref> however being on the eastern side of the storm, most of the damage came in the form of wind.\n\n=====Vermont=====\nAlmost every river and stream in [[Vermont]] flooded, resulting in at least three deaths and one missing.<ref name=\"ABC6\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=Irene inundates Vermont, washing out bridges, killing one|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2011/US/08/29/irene.vermont/index.html|publisher=CNN|accessdate=August 29, 2011|date=August 31, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Henson|first=Matt|title=WCAX viewers document deadly storm in Vt|url=http://www.wcax.com/story/15349160/wcax-viewers-document-deadly-storm-in-vt?redirected=true|accessdate=September 14, 2011|newspaper=WCAX News|date=August 28, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120406101403/http://www.wcax.com/story/15349160/wcax-viewers-document-deadly-storm-in-vt?redirected=true|archive-date=April 6, 2012|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In [[Wilmington, Vermont|Wilmington]], the flood level of the [[Deerfield River]] east branch reportedly exceeded levels measured during the [[1938 New England hurricane]] \u2013 the only other tropical cyclone to make a direct hit on Vermont in the state's recorded history.<ref>{{cite news|title=Vt. communities inundated by Irene flooding|url=http://www.wcax.com/story/15347599/wilmington-inundated-by-irene-flooding|accessdate=September 14, 2011|publisher=WCAX|location=Vermont|date=August 28, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110828212204/http://www.wcax.com/story/15347599/wilmington-inundated-by-irene-flooding|archive-date=August 28, 2011|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Throughout Vermont, numerous [[covered bridge]]s, many over 100 years old, were damaged or destroyed.<ref>{{cite news|last=Hallenbeck|first=Terri|title=Vermont's covered bridges take a hit from Irene|url=http://www.burlingtonfreepress.com/article/20110830/NEWS07/108300305/Vermont-s-covered-bridges-take-hit-from-Irene?odyssey=mod|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120729001220/http://www.burlingtonfreepress.com/article/20110830/NEWS07/108300305/Vermont-s-covered-bridges-take-hit-from-Irene?odyssey=mod|url-status=dead|archive-date=July 29, 2012|accessdate=September 14, 2011|newspaper=Burlington Free Press|date=August 30, 2011}}</ref> Extensive road damage resulted in the isolation of over a dozen rural towns that would require helicopter air-lifts of necessities in the days immediately following the storm.<ref>{{cite news|last=Gast|first=Phil|title=Crews reach far corners of Vermont cut off by Irene|url=http://www.cnn.com/2011/US/08/31/irene.vermont.towns/|accessdate=September 14, 2011|newspaper=CNN|date=September 1, 2011}}</ref> The storm decimated multiple sections of [[U.S. Route 4 in Vermont|U.S. Route 4]] between [[Rutland (city), Vermont|Rutland]] and [[Quechee, Vermont|Quechee]], making east/west travel through the southern part of state nearly impossible. The resort town of [[Killington, Vermont|Killington]] as well as neighboring [[Pittsfield, Vermont|Pittsfield]] were completely isolated from travel in and out for two weeks. Statewide, the cost of repairs for road and bridge damage alone was estimated to exceed $700 million.<ref>{{cite news|last=Kinzel|first=Bob|title=Road Repairs Will Top $700 Million, But Federal Aid Uncertain|url=http://www.vpr.net/news_detail/92103/|publisher=Vermont Public Radio|accessdate=October 7, 2011|date=September 27, 2011}}</ref>\n\nRelief concerts were organized by local Vermont bands such as [[Phish]]<ref>{{cite news|last=Pollak|first=Sally|title=Phish jams for flood relief in Vermont|url=http://www.burlingtonfreepress.com/article/20110914/NEWS02/110914015/Phish-jams-flood-relief-Vermont|publisher=Burlington Free Press|accessdate=October 7, 2011|date=September 15, 2011}}</ref> and [[Grace Potter and the Nocturnals]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Hallenbeck|first=Brent|title=Grace Potter to hold two flood relief benefits|url=http://www.burlingtonfreepress.com/article/20111006/ENT/111005023/1005/Grace-Potter-hold-two-flood-relief-benefits-|publisher=Burlington Free Press|accessdate=October 7, 2011|date=October 6, 2011}}</ref> By December the state was recovering more quickly than originally expected. Within a month of the storm 84 of 118 closed sections of state highway, and 28 of 34 bridges, had been reopened. The state had relied on assistance from [[National Guard of the United States|National Guard]] units in eight other states, and highway workers lent to it by New Hampshire and Maine. \"We'll do the work and we'll figure out how we're paying for it,\" said deputy state secretary of transportation [[Sue Minter]], \"but we're not waiting.\" Repair costs ultimately turned out to be $175\u2013200 million, with most of it covered by federal disaster relief.<ref name=\"NYT Vermont Irene recovery article\">{{cite news|last=Schwartz|first=John|title=Vermont Rebounding Quickly From Hurricane Irene|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/12/06/us/vermont-rebounding-from-hurricane-irene.html|newspaper=The New York Times|date=December 6, 2011|accessdate=December 6, 2011}}</ref>\n\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"100px\">\nFile:Tropical Storm Irene Flood-Buildings at Quechee Vermont 2011-08-28.jpg|Flood waters from Tropical Storm Irene on the Ottauquechee River in Quechee, Vermont.\nFile:Tropical Storm Irene Flood-Bridge at Quechee Vermont 2011-08-28.jpg|Flood waters on the Ottauquechee River in Quechee scouring the approach to the covered bridge, opposite side.\nFile:Tropical Storm Irene Damage-Bridge at Quechee Vermont 2011-10-23.jpg|Damage caused by flood waters to the Quechee covered bridge on the northern shore of the river.\nFile:Tropical Storm Irene Damage-Bridge at Taftsville Vermont 2012-05-03.jpg|Damage caused by flood waters on the Ottauquechee River to the Taftsville bridge.\nFile:Tropical Storm Irene Damage-Bridge Abutment Swept Away at Royalton Vermont 2011-09-07.jpg|Damage caused by flood waters on the White River to the Royalton, Vermont bridge.\n</gallery>\n\n===Maine===\n\nTropical storm conditions occurred throughout the state of Maine during Irene's passage.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/2011/graphics/al09/loop_S.shtml|title=Irene Graphics Archive|date=August 29, 2011|publisher=National Hurricane Center|accessdate=November 1, 2011}}</ref> Flooding caused by Irene's heavy rainfall washed out two bridges on [[Maine State Route 27|State Route 27]] in [[Carrabassett Valley, Maine|Carrabassett Valley]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sunjournal.com/franklin/story/1080326|title=Carrabassett Valley deals with aftermath of Hurricane Irene|last=Bryant|first=Ann|date=August 30, 2011|publisher=[[Sun Journal (Lewiston)|Sun Journal]]|accessdate=November 1, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Canada===\nIrene also affected a large section of Canada, stretching from the [[Eastern Ontario|eastern]] [[Ontario]] to the coasts of [[Newfoundland and Labrador]]. On August 28, in [[Quebec]], high winds (more than {{convert|110|kph|mph}} in some places) and heavy rainfall from post-tropical storm Irene knocked out power to over 250,000 homes, felled tree branches, and damaged buildings and traffic signals across [[Montreal]]. One person was killed after a road was washed out and cars were swept into the [[Yamaska River]] near [[Sorel-Tracy]]; another section of road in [[Charlevoix]] was also washed out, while flooding forced evacuations in [[Estrie]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/story/2011/08/28/ns-east-coast-irene.html|title=Irene drenches Quebec, Maritimes|accessdate=September 14, 2011|date=August 28, 2011|newspaper=CBC News}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cyberpresse.ca/international/dossiers/ouragan-irene/201108/28/01-4429581-irene-balaie-le-quebec-250-000-foyers-prives-delectricite.php|title=''Irene'' balaie le Qu\u00e9bec, 250 000 foyers priv\u00e9s d'\u00e9lectricit\u00e9|trans-title=Irene batters Quebec; 250,000 left without power|language=French|accessdate=September 14, 2011|date=August 28, 2011|newspaper=La Presse|location=Montreal}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/story/2011/08/29/irene-aftermath-quebec.html|title=Irene leaves a mark on Quebec|accessdate=September 14, 2011|date=August 29, 2011|newspaper=CBC News}}</ref> In [[New Brunswick]], many trees fell in the wake of the hurricane, mainly due to the strong winds associated with the storm. Power was lost to an estimated 75,000 \u2013 200,000 New Brunswick residents, directly due to the gale-force winds. Insured damage in Canada was estimated at $130 million.<ref name=ibcdamage/>\n\nDescribed as \"A photographic scavenger hunt set to a hurricane\", [[Wikipedia: Wikipedia Takes Montreal|Wikipedia Takes Montreal]] was held August 28, coinciding with the hurricane.\n\n==Retirement==\n{{See also|List of retired Atlantic hurricane names}}\nOwing to the high death toll and extensive damage wrought by the storm, the name ''Irene'' was later retired by the [[World Meteorological Organization]], and will never again be used for an [[Atlantic hurricane|Atlantic tropical cyclone]]. It was replaced for the [[2017 Atlantic hurricane season|2017 season]] with ''[[Hurricane Irma|Irma]]''.<!-- DO NOT ADD \"IRMA WAS LATER RETIRED AFTER THE 2017 ATLANTIC HURRICANE SEASON AND REPLACED WITH ''IDALIA'' FOR THE 2023 SEASON.\" IT HAS BEEN DEEMED IRRELEVANT! AND DO NOT REMOVE THE NOTE! --><ref>{{cite report|title=\"Irene\" retired from list of Atlantic Basin storm names|date=April 13, 2012|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|accessdate=April 13, 2012|url=http://www.noaanews.noaa.gov/stories2012/20120413_irene.html}}</ref>\n\n== Response efforts ==\n[[Direct Relief]], a disaster relief organization, among many other organizations, collaborated to offer assistance for people affected by Irene.<ref>{{Citation|chapter=Direct Relief|publisher=SAGE Publications, Inc.|isbn=9781412971010|doi=10.4135/9781412994064.n46|title=Encyclopedia of Disaster Relief|year=2011}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal bar|Tropical cyclones|Caribbean|United States}}\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[1806 Great Coastal hurricane]] <!-- (1806) - Category 2 hurricane sunk the Rose-in-Bloom, a ship that was made (possibly) out of wood -->\n* [[1821 Norfolk and Long Island hurricane]] <!-- (1821) \u2013 flooded the city to Canal Street -->\n* [[1938 New England hurricane]] <!-- (1938) - particularly damaging and fatal hurricane that impacted New England -->\n* [[Hurricane Bob]] <!-- (1991) - last hurricane to directly impact New England. it also impacted New Haven, CT -->\n* [[Hurricane Carol]] <!-- (1954) - caused significant damage to Rhode Island and Connecticut -->\n* [[Hurricane Connie]] <!-- (1955) \u2013 similar track through the mid-Atlantic, but farther west -->\n* [[Hurricane Diane]] <!-- (1955) \u2013 similar flood disaster in interior New England -->\n* [[Hurricane Floyd]] <!-- (1999) \u2013 last hurricane to produce significant damage to Eastern North Carolina and threaten New England -->\n* [[Hurricane Gloria]] <!-- (1985) \u2013 took a similar path through the East Coast -->\n* [[Hurricane Isabel]] <!-- (2003) \u2013 hurricane with similar path through North Carolina and Virginia -->\n* [[Hurricane Sandy]] <!-- (2012) \u2013 Hit a year later with even more power and intensity then Irene -->\n* [[List of New England hurricanes]]\n* [[List of New York hurricanes]]\n* [[List of New Jersey hurricanes]]\n* [[List of Pennsylvania hurricanes]]\n* [[List of Delaware hurricanes]]\n* [[List of Maryland hurricanes (1980\u2013present)|List of Maryland hurricanes]]\n* [[List of Canada hurricanes]]\n* [[List of costliest Atlantic hurricanes]]\n* [[List of retired Atlantic hurricane names]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=nb}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Hurricane Irene (2011)}}\n*[[National Hurricane Center]]'s [http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/2011/IRENE.shtml? advisory archive]\n*[[Hydrometeorological Prediction Center]]'s [http://www.wpc.ncep.noaa.gov/tropical/IRENE/IRENE_archive.shtml advisory archive]\n*[[NASA]]'s [http://www.nasa.gov/mission_pages/hurricanes/archives/2011/h2011_Irene.html storm data on Hurricane Irene]\n*[[Environment Canada]]'s [https://web.archive.org/web/20110611125232/http://www.atl.ec.gc.ca/weather/hurricane/bulletins_all_e.html#2011:Irene Advisory archive]\n\n{{Retired Atlantic hurricanes}}\n{{2011 Atlantic hurricane season buttons}}\n\n[[Category:Hurricane Irene| ]]\n[[Category:Category 3 Atlantic hurricanes|Irene]]\n[[Category:2011 disasters in Canada]]\n[[Category:2011 in Puerto Rico]]\n[[Category:2011 in the Bahamas]]\n[[Category:2011 in the British Virgin Islands]]\n[[Category:2011 in the Dominican Republic]]\n[[Category:2011 in the Turks and Caicos Islands]]\n[[Category:2011 in the United States Virgin Islands]]\n[[Category:Hurricanes in the Leeward Islands|Irene]]\n[[Category:Hurricanes in Guadeloupe|Irene]]\n[[Category: